<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Major Integrated Circuit Project Goes Smoothly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, July 24 (Xinhua) -- Construction of the Project 909
integrated circuit production lines has proceeded smoothly in the
New Pudong Area in Shanghai since its launching last year.
</P>
<P>
The first phase of the project is expected to be put into trial
operation by next February, half a year ahead of schedule.
</P>
<P>
The project is focused on building an 8-inch silicon
monocrystal production line for the Shanghai Huahong
NEC Electronics Co. Ltd.. The production line adopts
0.5-0.35-micron technology.
</P>
<P>
The line has been built completely for civil and commercial
use, with an expected monthly output of 20,000 pieces of 8-inch
silicon, according to official sources.
</P>
<P>
The Shanghai company has invested 500 million U.S. dollars in
the project, and the Japanese branch of NEC the remaining 200
million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Integrated circuit design and production lines are also
included in the project, according to official sources.
</P>
<P>
This project was launched to reduce China's heavy dependence on
foreign imports. In 1997 alone, the country imported 3.4 billion
U.S. dollars worth of integrated circuits, according to official
figures. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
