<HEADLINE> Clinton Expects Close Working Ties With Obuchi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 24 (xinhua) -- President Bill Clinton expects
close working relationship with Keizo Obuchi, Japan's foreign
minister but now prime minister-designate following his election
as the leader of the Liberal Democratic Party, the White House
said Friday.
</P>
<P>
"The president believes that he can forge a close working
relationship with Foreign Minister Obuchi if he is confirmed as
prime minister," spokesman Mike McCurry said.
</P>
<P>
Obuchi was elected as the leader of the Liberal Democratic
party Friday -- a move that assures he will formally become the
nation's next prime minister.
</P>
<P>
Obuchi has said he intends to act quickly to deal with Japan's
economic problems.
</P>
<P>
"The government of Japan knows seriously we take the
commitments Japan has made to economic modernization," McCurry
said.
</P>
<P>
"It is not our place to comment on the ability of a prime
minister to promulgate a program," McCurry said when asked if the
United States was confident Obuchi would achieve his goals.
</P>
</TEXT>
