<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam Establishes "Agent Orange Victims Fund" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, July 24 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam established the "Agent
Orange Victims Fund " (AGORAVIF) Friday, in order to help the
hundreds of thousands people who suffered the toxic chemical used
by the United States forces in the Vietnam War.
</P>
<P>
The chemical war conducted by the United States between 1961
and 1971 was the biggest war of destruction against the ecology
and human beings in the history of war of humankind, said Nguyen
Trong Nhan, president of the Vietnam Red Cross, and management
council president of the AGORAVIF. He was speaking at the
inauguration ceremony of the fund.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. armed forces dropped 5,700 tons of agent orange in
South Vietnam during the war, affecting hundred of thousands of
people, said Nhan.
</P>
<P>
Many people affected by the toxic chemical contracted serious
and even fatal illness including cancer. Others gave birth to
deformed children and the effects were passed on to a younger
generation.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. forces sprayed agent orange, a kind of herbicide
packed in containers with orange strips, on a large area of
Vietnam to defoliate the dense jungles which protected the North
Vietnamese troops and their resupply convoys from being exposed.
</P>
<P>
Nhan said that although more than 20 years had passed since the
end of the war, agent orange, which can remain in soil for a very
long time, is still causing serious consequences in the lives and
health of Vietnamese people.
</P>
<P>
Nhan expressed hope that the fund will receive positive
responses from local and foreign organizations and individuals to
alleviate the losses and misery of agent orange victims.
</P>
<P>
Do Muoi, the Vietnamese Communist Party Central Committee's
adviser, and honorary president of the Vietnam Red Cross, Nhuyen
Thi Binh, Vice Vietnamese president, and other leaders attended
the fund's inauguration. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
