<HEADLINE> UK Gov't Rules Out Pardon for WWI Executed Soldiers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 24 (Xinhua) -- The British government Friday ruled
out the possibility of a blanket pardon for 306 British soldiers
who were executed for desertion during World War I.
</P>
<P>
British Armed Forces Minister John Reid told parliament the
passage of time meant grounds for a pardon on the basis of unsafe
conviction "just did not exist."
</P>
<P>
"In the vast majority of cases, there is little to be gleaned
from the fragments of the stories that would provide serious
grounds for legal pardon," Reid said.
</P>
<P>
However, the minister expressed "deep sense of regret at this
loss of life, calling these soldiers "victims, with million of
others, of a cataclysmic and ghastly war."
</P>
<P>
Reid also noted that the Labor government would abolish the
death penalty for military offenses in the armed forces.
</P>
<P>
Some descendants of those executed soldiers and the Royal
British Legion veterans group have campaigned for many years for a
blanket pardon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
