<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Angola in Critical Situation: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, July 24 (Xinhua) -- Angolan Interior Minister Pitra
Petroff said here Friday that the country has been plunged into
great tension since the killing of civilians in northeast Angola
by the National Union for the Total Independence of Angola
(UNITA) Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The situation is worrying, Petroff said. But he said that the
situation is still under the government control.
</P>
<P>
The Angolan minister made the remarks to the press before
leaving for Cape Verde.
</P>
<P>
UNITA militiamen attacked Bula Town in Lunda-Norte Province
Wednesday, killing at least 124 people including foreigners,
according to Angolan army headquarters.
</P>
<P>
Lunda-Norte governor Gomes Maiato told the state radio that a
batch of UNITA fighters started shooting unarmed residents who
were doing business in local market at around 21:00 (GMT)
Wednesday, killing 127 and wounding 75.
</P>
<P>
Of the wounded, 40 were sent to a Luanda hospital Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Angolan military sources believed this is the worst killing by
UNITA since the Lusaka Peace Accorded was signed in 1994.
</P>
<P>
Reports said UNITA forces ambushed traveling vehicles Thursday
in central Angola's Kuanza-Sul Province, killing nine, including
seven civilians and two policemen, and injuring scores of others.
</P>
<P>
A few days ago, Angolan President Eduardo dos Santos said
UNITA has actually launched "an declared war".
</P>
<P>
Defense Minister Pedro Sebastiao warned that the government
army will fight back in an appropriate way if UNITA initiates any
large-scale military operations.  
</P>
</TEXT>
