<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Criticized for Raising Controversial Issues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, July 24 (Xinhua) -- An Iranian conservative leader
criticized the European Union (EU) on Friday for raising several
controversial issues during its recent talks with Iran.
</P>
<P>
"The EU must not tell us out of the blue that we are
terrorists, or supporters of terrorists or are seeking to obtain
nuclear weapons," secretary of the conservative Guardians Council
Ayatollah Ahmad Jannati said at the Friday prayers congregation.
</P>
<P>
"If you (EU) want to deal with us in this spirit, it would be
unacceptable to our people, to our government and to our leader,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
A delegation comprising officials from Britain, Austria and
Germany, the past, present and future EU presidents, opened a new
round of talks with Iranian officials in Tehran on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The EU delegation exchanged views with Iranian officials about
terrorism, weapons of mass destruction, the Middle East peace
process, human rights and other regional and international issues.
</P>
<P>
The EU called on Iran to nullify the award offered for those
who will kill the British writer Salman Rushdie according to a
fatwa, or religious decree by late Iranian leader Ayatollah Musavi
Khomeini. It also asked Tehran to change its stance towards Israel.
</P>
<P>
Jannati said that the Rushdie issue was definitively decided
by Khomeini and no one has the authority to revoke his fatwa.
</P>
<P>
He said that the EU must admit that the issue was definitively
decided once and for all, and they should not dwell on the topic
in their meetings here and there anymore.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian official noted that the EU must accept as a fact
Iran's position towards Israel, saying that "we believe that
Israel is a usurper, and Muslim occupied lands must be liberated."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
