<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Monitors Encouraged by Election Process in Cambodia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, July 24 (Xinhua) -- The monitor group for
Cambodia's July 26 general elections said Friday it was encouraged
by the smoothness of the registration and campaign process, the
two main phases of the elections.
</P>
<P>
The Joint International Observer Group (JIOG) will observe and
judge the polling process Friday evening.
</P>
<P>
In a statement after the month-long campaign ended Friday, the
group said it had been "generally encouraged" by the way the
registration process was carried out and by the good result.
</P>
<P>
About 95 percent or more of the total population was registered
for the elections.
</P>
<P>
The result "gives a clear signal to Cambodian leaders and the
international community alike that the Cambodian people are
determined to use this opportunity to decide their own political
future," the group said.
</P>
<P>
As for the campaign, the group called it "active." It said the
parties, to a large extent, were able to hold their rallies,
disseminate information about their programs and pursue other
relevant political meeting and rallies.
</P>
<P>
The group was still concerned about some problems such as
unresolved killings, intimidation, voters' beliefs in the secrecy
of the ballot, ethnic prejudices and unequal access to electronic
media.
</P>
<P>
The monitors said many of the problems seemed to be of a
practical and technical nature.
</P>
<P>
It felt "justified in anticipating that reasonable conditions
exist for an election on Sunday July 26, that can broadly
represent the will of the Cambodian people," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The group hoped the election process would be free from any
kinds of violence that could disturb the electoral process and
influence its final assessment in a negative way. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
