<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bahrain: Its Citizen Not A Spy as Said </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, July 24 (Xinhua) -- A Bahraini envoy denied here Friday
that a Bahraini citizen found dead in Lebanon is an intelligence
officer sent to observe Bahraini opposition groups in Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon's Voice of the People radio quoted Abdul al Aziz Ali,
Bahraini ambassador to Syria as saying that Toufic Abel-Meneen
Ibrahim is an ordinary person without any official link.
</P>
<P>
Ibrahim was found dead in a tourist area of Beirut on Sunday
with a pistol in his hand.
</P>
<P>
After meeting with Lebanese Foreign Ministry's
Secretary-General Zafer Hassan, Ali told reporters that according
to the legal medical examination, Ibrahim killed himself because
of financial difficulties.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon earlier insisted that Ibrahim is a Bahraini
intelligence agent charged with observing Bahrain's opposition
groups in Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Ali arrived in Lebanon on Friday to handle the issue as there
is no Bahraini embassy in Beirut.
</P>
<P>
He said he has delivered a message from the Bahraini
government to the Lebanese government over the issue, adding the
good ties between the two countries will not be affected by the
incident.
</P>
<P>
But there has not been an official comment from the Lebanese
government on Ali's claims. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980725.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya Drops Fraud Charges on Treasury Chiefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 24 (Xinhua) -- Kenya Friday dropped fraud
charges against four treasury chiefs and 11 officials and
businessmen, less than 24 hours after their arrests.
</P>
<P>
"I have instructions to enter a nolle prosequi (termination of
prosecution) in this case, and hereby do," Director of Public
Prosecutions (DPP) Bernard Chunga said in a written presentation
to Nairobi Chief Magistrate Uniter Kidullah.
</P>
<P>
Kidullah issued an order Thursday to arrest Kenya Revenue
Authority (KRA) Commissioner-General John Msafari, Commissioner of
Customs Samuel Chebii, Financial Secretary Joseph KanKyi Kinyua,
Director of Fiscal and Monetary Affairs Njeru Kirira and 11 other
senior Customs officials.
</P>
<P>
Kidullah said his move followed of the application by the
Director of the Kenya Anti-Corruption Authority (KACA), John
Harun Mwau.
</P>
<P>
However, under the Kenyan law, the DPP can terminate any
criminal charges on the instructions of the attorney-general who
is not required by law to explain his actions.
</P>
<P>
Chunga said the Criminal Investigations Department (CID) would
probe the case and report to the attorney-general.
</P>
<P>
The officials were accused of defrauding the government
through failure to levy taxes on sugar and wheat imported from
Brazil and Argentina. The frauds involved more than 230 million
Shillings (some 3.9 million U.S. Dollars).
</P>
<P>
They are also to be charged with breaching the public trust by
fraudulently allowing 1,400 tons of uninspected sugar into the
country's market.
</P>
<P>
Failure to collect tax on illegal sugar imports was a key
complaint by the International Monetary Fund (IMF) when it
suspended a major loan to Kenya in July last year. The IMF has
also asked for reforming KRA.
</P>
<P>
Other IMF demands, agreed with the government in last August,
included the setting up of an independent anti-corruption
authority, reform of the energy sector and investigation of past
abuses of public funds.
</P>
<P>
KACA was set up last December under Mwau, an ex-policeman and
former presidential candidate. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980725.0018 </DOCNO>
