<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India Ascertaining Reports on U.S. Decision to Expel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, July 24 (Xinhua) -- India said Friday it was
ascertaining reports on decision of the Clinton Administration to
ask Indian scientists to leave the country.
</P>
<P>
"We are ascertaining the facts. If it has happened, it is
unfortunate," said a spokesman of the Ministry for External
Affairs.
</P>
<P>
Reports from Washington said that the Clinton Administration
has asked 7 Indian scientists working in the United States to
leave the country and 75 others are likely to be forced out in
what is seen as a punitive action against India for its nuclear
tests in May.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. has also reportedly ordered suspension of all
interactions with India and Pakistan financed by the Department of
Energy and national laboratories except for humanitarian
assistance.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. has denied visa to Chairman of Indian Atomic Energy
Commission R. Chidambaram and may ask all Indian scientists
working in the country on exchange and fellowship programs to
return home.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. actions have set off strong repercussions in the
Indian Parliament with a parliamentarian suggesting to shift the
headquarters of the United Nations from New York to Africa or Asia
where India could be one of the choices.
</P>
<P>
Members of Parliament from nearly all parties condemned the
U.S. decision as unfortunate, saying Indian scientists made
significant contribution to science and technology in the U.S.
</P>
<P>
The Press Trust of India reported from the southern city of
Bangalore that some top scientists described the U.S. decision as
"unjustified and unwarranted". 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
