<DOCNO> XIE19980725.0023 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia, U.S. Sign Accords on Ties, Nuclear Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 24 (Xinhua) -- Russian Prime Minister Sergei
Kiriyenko and U.S. Vice President Al Gore signed here Friday
several documents on bilateral ties and nuclear cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Their meetings were held within the framework of the
U.S.-Russian Joint Commission on Economic and Technological
Cooperation. Both were chairmen of the commission that was
established in 1993.
</P>
<P>
The documents include a joint statement on economic and
technological cooperation, a joint statement on helping Russia's
closed nuclear towns and an agreement on the management of
plutonium that has been withdrawn from nuclear military programs.
</P>
<P>
At a joint press conference following their meetings, both Gore
and Kiriyenko expressed satisfaction with what they described as
"constructive," "frank and friendly" talks.
</P>
<P>
Gore reaffirmed U.S. support for Russia's efforts to accelerate
reform and its integration into the global economy.
</P>
<P>
Under the so-called Nuclear Cities Initiative, the United
States would help Russia's closed nuclear complex to find civilian
jobs for its employees and commercially viable projects to produce
civilian goods and services.
</P>
<P>
Although no figure of funding is included in the joint
statement, Russian Atomic Energy Minister Yevgeny Adamov said
Washington has agreed to provide 25-30 million U.S. dollars next
year in aid for the nuclear towns such as Sarov, the leading
Russian nuclear weapons research center.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday, thousands of employees in Sarov staged a
three-hour warning strike for back wages, fueling concern about
safety at the nuclear facilities.
</P>
<P>
During his stay of some 24 hours, Gore also had a telephone
conversation with Russian President Boris Yeltsin, who is spending
his vacation in Shuiskaya Chupa, Karelia, and discussed U.S.
President Bill Clinton's upcoming visit to Russia in September.
</P>
<P>
Kiriyenko and Gore also discussed the state of Russia's economy
and the help provided by the international financial institutions.
Washington was a strong backer of a 22.6 billion dollar bailout
loan package for Russia, finalized earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
On space cooperation, Russian Space Agency director general
Yuri Koptov told reporters that Kiriyenko reaffirmed Moscow's
pledge to continue its participation in the construction of the
Alpha international space station.
</P>
<P>
Gore, who arrived here Thursday evening, was scheduled to leave
Moscow later Friday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980725.0024 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Qian, Cuban Foreign Minister Meet in Havana </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, July 24 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Vice Premier Qian Qichen
and Cuban Foreign Minister Robert Robaina Friday expressed their
confidence that bigger progress will be made in developing
relations between their countries.
</P>
<P>
The two officials discussed bilateral relations and
international issues of common concern during a meeting, a Chinese
Foreign Ministry spokesman told Chinese reporters.
</P>
<P>
Qian's visit is important not only to Cuba but also to the
Caribbean region, said Robaina.
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister highly praised the development of the
friendly relationship between his country and China, saying that
exchange of visits by top leaders of the two countries has helped
push the relations to a new level.
</P>
<P>
In November 1993, Chinese President Jiang Zemin visited Cuba
while Cuban leader Fidel Castro visited China in 1995.
</P>
<P>
In the past few years, the relations between the two countries
are developing in all areas and have entered a new period, Qian
told Robaina.
</P>
<P>
The two officials expressed their satisfaction with the
development of the bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
Qian said that China attaches great importance to the
relationship with Cuba and is willing to strengthen it.
</P>
<P>
Qian also expressed the Chinese government's gratitudes to Cuba
for its support on many issues, particularly in helping develop
the relations between China and the Caribbean nations. Robaina
expressed thanks for China's precious support on the international
stage.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese vice premier praised the outstanding achievement
made by the Cuban people in social and economic development under
pressure from outside.
</P>
<P>
This year, Cuba has achieved some significant progress in
foreign policy, gaining more understanding and sympathy from the
international community and having more influence on international
affairs, said Qian.
</P>
<P>
Qian expressed his belief that the Cuban people will overcome
difficulties and make more progress.
</P>
<P>
Following the meeting, Chinese Vice Foreign Minister Yang
Jiechi and Jorge Luis Aspiolea, director of the National Hydrology
Institution of Cuba, signed an agreement on technology and
economic cooperation between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Qian, who arrived here Thursday, will leave Saturday for
Jamaica, the last leg of his five-Caribbean-nation tour, which
also includes Barbados and Guyana. 
</P>
</TEXT>
