<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uganda Sets Up Fish Storage Facility at Airport </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Kampala, July 24 (Xinhua) -- A new cold fish storage facility
has been set up at Entebbe international airport following the
recent lifting of the European Union's (EU) ban on fish products
from Uganda.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Kintu Musoke commissioned the facility
Thursday, Radio Uganda reported Friday evening.
</P>
<P>
He commended the Entebbe Handling Services for completing the
project earlier than expected and hoped dealers in the fisheries
industry will make full use of the new storage system.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Works, Housing and Communications John Nasasira
urged the management to ensure the facility, which cost 630
million Uganda shillings ( 500,000 U.S. Dollars), is run and
maintained professionally.
</P>
<P>
At the end of 1997, the EU imposed a ban on fish imports from
East African countries following an outbreak of cholera in the
region and reported use of chemicals in the Lake Victoria to kill
weeds hampering fishing activities.
</P>
<P>
On July 1, Uganda was allowed to export fish to European
market because it had met a signficant part of EU standards.
</P>
<P>
Uganda's fish processing sector has expanded greatly in recent
years and current export earnings are in excess of 100 million
dollars per year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
