<DOCNO> XIE19980725.0032 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe to Boost Steel Production </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 24 (Xinhua) -- The Zimbabwean government is
taking steps to ensure the operations of the crucial iron and
steel industry are viable, president Robert Mugabe said Friday.
</P>
<P>
Officially opening the eight million U.S. Dollar steel makers
of hot rolling mills in Redcliff of central Zimbabwe, Mugabe said
measures were being implemented to remove hurdles dogging the
industry, the Zimbabwe News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
"The government has embarked on the rehabilitation of blast
furnace number four of the Zimbabwe Steel Company (ZISCO) to
ensure an adequate supply of billets and scrap metal for
steelmakers," he said.
</P>
<P>
The rebuilding of the blast furnace would involve the
restoration of the furnace to a production capacity of 700,000
metric tons of liquid steel per annum, he said.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Ferrostal AG of Germany had been selected as
ZISCO's technical partner to modernise and automate steel-making
and casting operations, he said.
</P>
<P>
"Once the rehabilitation of these projects is completed,
possibly within the next 12 to 18 months," Mugabe said, "ZISCO
will become a viable steel producer". 
</P>
</TEXT>
