<DOCNO> XIE19980725.0034 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Northeastern Somalia Elects Local Leaders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, July 24 (Xinhua) -- A controversial conference in
northeastern Somalia has elected a "president" and a
"vice-president".
</P>
<P>
The 70-day conference concluded Thursday in Garowe District of
Nugal region, electing Colonel Abdullahi Yussuf Ahmed and Mohamed
Abdi Hashi as "president and vice-president" respectively.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 300 people from various sectors of the northeastern
communities attended the meeting aimed at establishing a local
government as Puntland.
</P>
<P>
Chairman of the conference Islan Mohamed Islam Muse also
endorsed the formation of a 69-member "parliament" and nine
"ministers" to be announced within 45 days beginning from
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
According to the information from Garowe town, the two
leaders, General Mohamed Abshir Musa and Boqor Kingkong, held a
press meeting Friday, condemning the outcome of the conference
and calling it a meaningless political maneuver mal-organized by
Colonel Yussuf.
</P>
<P>
Sources told Xinhua that the two leaders were especially
annoyed by the election of Colonel Yussuf as a "president" and
proposal of Garowe town as "the capital city" for the autonomous
administration.
</P>
<P>
General Musa and Boqor Kingkong prefer the port town of
Bossaso, the largest city in the northeastern Somalia, as the
"capital city."
</P>
<P>
According to the politicians in northeastern Somalia, the
conference which has overcome serious disputes over how the
delegates would be put into equilibrium in its embryonic stages
had been a political gamble played by Colonel Yussuf in his
attempts to overthrow General Musa whom they bitterly
misunderstood during the meeting in Cairo attended by the Somali
faction leaders late last year.
</P>
<P>
The politicians said that the meeting had all the time been
supporting Colonel Yussuf.
</P>
<P>
The outcome of the meeting has shocked thousands of people in
Bossaso and several other major towns in the northeast.
</P>
<P>
The politicians have warned against insecurity which may
result unless the traditional leaders face the problem deeply.
</P>
<P>
Colonel Yussuf had abandoned the Cairo meeting while General
Musa had signed the Cairo peace deal together with Ali Mahdi
Mohamed and Hussein Mohamed Aidid.
</P>
<P>
General Musa and Colonel Yussuf had represented the Somali
Salvation Democratic Front in the Cairo peace deal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
