<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uganda Wildlife Authority to Translocate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Kampala, July 24 (Xinhua) -- Uganda Wildlife Authority (UWA)
has clarified its position on translocation of elephants which
are reported to have caused loss of life and destruction to
property in Luwero district in the central part of the country.
</P>
<P>
A statement recently signed by the Acting Executive Director
of UWA Yakobo Moyini said the UWA is trying its best to have the
elephants moved to their new homes in the northern sector of
Murchison Falls national park, Radio Uganda reported Friday
evening.
</P>
<P>
UWA has stationed staff on the ground to keep monitoring the
big animals and is trying to procure the necessary equipment
including big containers to carry the elephants.
</P>
<P>
The director assured the local people that enough fund had
been secured and the job was to be done soon.
</P>
<P>
The general public have been urged to report any imminent
danger from the elephants to the Senior Warden who is now camped
at Kyakapimpini and is fully equipped.
</P>
<P>
The elephants, estimated to be about 60, are reported to
damage the crops and stroll in vallages, posing a great threat to
people's safety.
</P>
<P>
An elephant translocation expert from Zimbabwe has been in
Uganda since July 11 to acquaint himself with the situation
before embarking on translocation of these jumbos.
</P>
<P>
Local people are pressing the wildlife authority to move the
elephants as quickly as possible because the coming of the next
rainy season will make it more difficult.
</P>
<P>
Rain is expected at the end of this month, almost a month
earlier than usual.
</P>
<P>
However, an expert said the exact number, age and sex of the
elephants have to be established and access roads have to be
built for trucks to move the elephants. They have to be
tranquilized before being loaded on the trucks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
