<DOCNO> XIE19980725.0036 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Formal Mechanism Expected for Coop Between East </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, July 24 (Xinhua) - A senior official of the
East African Cooperation (EAC) said in Arusha Friday that the
three member states hope to establish a formal mechanism to boost
bilateral cooperation with the United States.
</P>
<P>
Jakaya Kikwete, chairman of the permanent tripartite
commission of the EAC, was quoted by sources as saying that
following an EAC-U.S. ministerial meeting in Entebbe, Uganda
during the recent visit by U.S. President Bill Clinton, "there is
need to establish a formal mechanism for regular EAC-US
ministerial consultations."
</P>
<P>
Kikwete, who is also the Minister for Foreign Affairs and
International Cooperation of Tanzania, made the remarks during
his meeting at the EAC headquarters with Richard Bogosian, a
senior official of the United States Agency for International
Development (USAID).
</P>
<P>
Bogosian said that the U.S. viewed the EAC, which consists of
the Kiswahili-speaking Tanzania, Kenya and Uganda, as a "very
serious undertaking", noting that the regional integration effort
was gaining momentum.
</P>
<P>
"The regional body deserve more attention by the United
States," he said, emphasizing the need for effective involvement
of the private sector and the civil society in the regional
integration process.
</P>
<P>
The meeting discussed a wide range of issues including
EAC-U.S. cooperation, food security and conflict resolution in
the Great Lakes region and prospect of enlarging the EAC
cooperation with Rwanda and Burundi.
</P>
<P>
Kikwete, accompanied by the EAC Executive Secretary Francis
Muthaura, told Bogosian together with J. Strauss, USAID
Coordinator in Tanzania, that EAC's priority was given to
economic cooperation and particularly the establishment of a
single market to benefit the three member states.
</P>
<P>
"The EAC is a binding and stabilizing factor ensuring healthy
economic cooperation and greater political cooperation in the
region," he said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this week, the permanent secretaries responsible for
foreign affairs in Tanzania, Kenya and Uganda agreed in a draft
memorandum of understanding that they will take concrete measures
to promote their cooperation in the foreign field in a bid to
enhance their image in the world arena.
</P>
<P>
The member states will establish liaison offices in their
foreign ministries with attention on aspects relating to foreign
affairs, making joint briefings, and soliciting support for the
EAC regional projects.
</P>
<P>
"They will provide consular services on behalf of the other
member states where they do not have embassies and consulates,
including renewal of passports and any other necessary assistance
to nationals of member states," the memorandum said.
</P>
<P>
It further said that the EAC members should cooperate in
multilateral diplomacy with a view to harmonizing policies with
the Organization of African Unity (OAU), the Abuja Treaty for
African Economic Community, the Nonaligned Movement, the Group of
77 and the (British) Commonwealth.
</P>
<P>
The memorandum also proposed collaboration by member states in
trade, investment, tourism as well as cultural activities.
</P>
<P>
In April, the three EAC member states approved a draft treaty
in a move to upgrade their cooperation into a treaty level to
help define in more clearer terms the shape and inclination of
the cooperation aimed at establishing a single market and
investment area in east Africa.
</P>
<P>
The EAC was founded on the basis of the defunct East African
Community which collapsed in 1977 due to reasons including the
divergence of economic policies then pursued by the member
states, the continued perception of disproportionate sharing of
benefits and lack of adequate compensation mechanisms.
</P>
<P>
Since its foundation in 1996, the new EAC has tried to address
the shortcomings inherent in the past cooperation initiatives and
determined to place the new regional integration on a sustainable
basis.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
