<HEADLINE> Burundi Armed Group Denies Involvement in Rebel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, July 24 (Xinhua) -- An armed group of
PALIPEHUTU has distanced itself from a rebel attack near
Bujumbura, capital of Burundi, in which 20 people were reportedly
killed Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The leader of PALIPEHUTU, Sezoya Antoine, who is attending the
second round of Burundi peace talks in north Tanzanian town of
Arusha, said Friday in a statement that his army has nothing to
do with the attack.
</P>
<P>
"We're totally dissociated from the attack which killed nearly
20 people near Bujumbura on Wednesday," Antoine said.
</P>
<P>
He also claimed that PALIPEHUTU had stopped armed hostilities
since July 20 to help the resumption of the second round of
Burundi peace talks chaired by the international mediator on
Burundi, Julius Nyerere, former president of Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
"We want everybody to respect the peace agreement signed here
last month by all the parties," Antoine said in his statement.
</P>
<P>
According to reports reaching here, the leader also said that
he has commanded his army to stop fighting unless an order is
given.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Burundi peace talks continued to make progress
Friday as all warring parties began closed-door and face-to-face
discussion on the root of the Burundi conflict.
</P>
<P>
The talks bring the government of Pierre Buyoya, who took
power in a July 1996 coup, face to face with Hutu rebels who are
fighting the country's Tutsi-dominated army.
</P>
<P>
The top agenda, the rules and procedures of negotiations, will
be tackled later after the negotiating team of Nyerere completed
drawing the procedures.
</P>
<P>
Nyerere's team is helped by nominated members from each of the
19 parties taking part in the peace talks to end ethnic violence
in the tiny central African republic which has claimed more than
150,000 lives since 1993.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for Nyerere, Hashim Mbita, said that the session
on Friday afternoon was adjourned to allow Nyerere and his team
to draw rules and procedures of the negotiations. Journalists
were not allowed to attend the session.
</P>
<P>
Delegates, however, tipped that Mathias Himita, Chairman of
PRP (one of the parties at the talks) said that absence of a king
in Burundi had led to such a brutal ethnic violence.
</P>
<P>
Sylvestre Ntibantunganya, former president of Burundi, claimed
in his half-an-hour presentation that previous insincerity of
governments had plunged the land-locked country into an
unprecedented crisis between Hutus and Tutsis.  
</P>
</TEXT>
