<HEADLINE> Clinton Expects Close Working Ties with Obuchi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 24 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
expects close working relationship with Keizo Obuchi, Japan's
foreign minister but now prime minister-designate following his
election as the leader of the Liberal Democratic Party, the White
House said on Friday.
</P>
<P>
"The president believes that he can forge a close working
relationship with Foreign Minister Obuchi if he is confirmed as
prime minister," spokesman Mike McCurry said.
</P>
<P>
Obuchi was elected as the leader of the Liberal Democratic
Party on Friday -- a move that assures he will formally become
the nation's next prime minister.
</P>
<P>
Obuchi has said he intends to act quickly to deal with
Japan's economic problems.
</P>
<P>
"The government of Japan knows seriously we take the
commitments Japan has made to economic modernization," McCurry
said.
</P>
<P>
"It is not our place to comment on the ability of a prime
minister to promulgate a program," McCurry said when asked if
the United States was confident Obuchi would achieve his goals.
</P>
<P>
McCurry, however, urged Obuchi to take bold and decisive steps
to revive the country's moribund economy and speed the pace of
banking sector reform.
</P>
<P>
"It's very critical that the new government move quickly and
with some measure of boldness to develop decisive action to
address the problems of the banking system and to restore rebust
domestic and demand-led growth to the Japanese economy," he said.
</P>
<P>
the White House press secretary said the United States looked
forward to Obuchi's economic action plans in the coming weeks.
</P>
<P>
"Some of the positions that he has announced in the past few
days, particularly in the area of fiscal policy, seem to us
promising ... But it's important that those words be followed up
with concrete action," he said.
</P>
<P>
Asked when Obuchi and Clinton would meet, McCurry said: "We
will look for a mutually convenient time and hopefully an early
and convenient time to meet with the new prime minister."
</P>
<P>
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright could hold talks at an
Association of South East Asian Nations (ASEAN) meeting in
Manila, McCurry said. Obuchi will attend an ASEAN Regional Forum
banquet on Sunday.  
</P>
</TEXT>
