<BODY>
<HEADLINE> European Telescope Sees Pattern in The Cosmic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 24 (Xinhua) -- The European infrared space
telescope finds a new population of galaxies, the first objects
known to contribute to the background glow of the universe,
according to a press release from the European Space Agency (ESA).
</P>
<P>
A team of French astronomers using the ESA's ISO space
telescope has detected two dozen distant galaxies that are
undergoing a process of intense evolution, either merging to build
larger ones or reaching their final shape.
</P>
<P>
These are the first individual objects known to contribute
their energy to the bulk of the Cosmic Infrared Background, a
radiation that fills the entire universe like a wallpaper, emitted
at the era when galaxies were formed.
</P>
<P>
The new-found distant galaxies are indeed like the "pattern" in
this "cosmic wallpaper".
</P>
<P>
This discovery will for the first time enable scientists to
test different theories of galaxy formation, and therefore have a
better understanding of the birth process of galaxies.
</P>
<P>
How the galaxies are born remained a mystery so far, mainly
because current telescopes cannot reach that far back in time,
about 12,000 million years ago.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980725.0042 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-25 </DATE_TIME>
