<HEADLINE> Seven Indian Scientists Asked to Leave U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 24 (Xinhua) -- Seven Indian scientists
have been asked to leave the United States because of sanctions
imposed on India for its nuclear tests in May, a government
research center said on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The scientists have been working at the National Institute of
Standards and Technology (NIST) in Gaithersburg, Maryland, on
two semiconductor manufacturing projects and a ceramics
processing project, said NIST spokesman Michael Newman.
</P>
<P>
The State Department has blacklisted these three projects and
has put on hold four projects NIST is running in conjunction
with the Indian National Physical Laboratory, all related to
scientific standards.
</P>
<P>
"We were asked to provide the State Department with a list of
projects in which researchers from Indian institutions are
taking part. We were given back a list with markings as to who
should leave and who could stay," Newman said
</P>
<P>
Pakistan, which responded to India with its own nuclear tests,
is also liable to the same sanctions.
</P>
<P>
The Department of Energy (DOE) said in a factsheet that the
sanctions required the suspension of all DOE-financed activities
with Indian or Pakistani government entities, except for
humanitarian assistance.
</P>
<P>
All visits by Indians and Pakistanis from the blacklisted
institutions must also be suspended, along with high-level visit
to India and Pakistan by DOE personnel, it said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
