<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Demilitarization in Africa Depends on Economic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, July 24 (Xinhua) -- Zanzibar President Salmin
Amour said Friday that the best option for demilitarization in
Africa is to get rid of poverty through developing economy.
</P>
<P>
Amour said this at the close of an international conference on
Africa's demilitarization in Arusha, northern Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
"It is very necessary for African leadership to pay more
attention towards uplifting the economic performances and direct
the national incomes to the well-being of the people," sources
quoted Amour as telling more than 100 senior military experts and
politicians from Africa and other parts of the world.
</P>
<P>
The Zanzibar president said that too much emphasis on war
would erode the meager resources, but too little preparation for
war may also make Africa vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
"It is advisable that a careful balance must be drawn in order
to have both the necessities complimenting each other," President
Amour said. "Even a small but well equipped army needs huge sum
of money."
</P>
<P>
Amour urged the African leaders to formulate new economic
strategies of competitiveness in the globalized world trade and
to set up a common defense mechanism to protect the stability in
the continent.
</P>
<P>
The three-day Conference on Leadership Challenges of
Demilitarization in Africa was organized by the Arias Foundation
for Peace and Human Progress in collaboration with the African
Leadership Forum and the United Nations Development Program.
</P>
<P>
The delegates, including former Haitian President
Jean-Bertrand Aristide and former President of Panama Guillermo
Ondara.
</P>
<P>
In his key-note address to open the conference Wednesday,
former president of Costa Rica Oscar Arias called on the
industrialized countries, especially the United States to stop
pouring their arms to the poor African continent.
</P>
<P>
Tanzanian President Benjamin Mkapa urged in his opening speech
African countries to cut down on military expenditures and to
promote their economies.
</P>
<P>
"The military expenses must reflect a realistic assessment of
external threat, if any, or the amount of resources at disposal,"
Mkapa said.
</P>
<P>
The best way to decrease military expenditures is to promote
the socio-economic development which demand infusion of greater
resources both private and official, he said.
</P>
<P>
However, Mkapa said, the aid from the developed countries to
Africa has drastically dropped from a total of 368 billion U.S.
Dollars in 1996 to 272 billion U.S. Dollars in 1997.
</P>
<P>
"Aid from the richest countries, G7, is a mere 0.19 percent of
their collective national incomes, far below the target of 0.7
percent set by the United Nations," he said.
</P>
<P>
Mkapa underscored that African countries should build a
consensus that a speedy socio-economic development will help
Africa to boost its capacity to move from confrontations and
wars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980725.0045 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-25 </DATE_TIME>
