<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Serious in Fighting AIDS </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 24 (Xinhua) -- The Zimbabwean government will
adopt a multi-sectorial approach through social mobilization and
advocacy to effectively combat the AIDS pandemic, a minister of
state said Friday.
</P>
<P>
Oppah Muchinguri, minister in the President's Office
responsible for gender issues, said this when she officially
opened a workshop to map out a program of action following the
recent Ugandan HIV/AIDS educational trip.
</P>
<P>
"AIDS is no longer just a ministry of health and child welfare
concern, but a problem affecting all sections of society," she
said, adding that "combating it requires a collective
comprehensive approach."
</P>
<P>
She said that women and children suffered most as a result of
the pandemic.
</P>
<P>
The Ugandan minister said that 25.84 percent of sexually
active adults between 15 and 49 were HIV positive. Also infected
were 720,000 women and 57,000 children.
</P>
<P>
Since 1985, she said, Zimbabwe has had an estimated 650,000
cumulative AIDS cases.
</P>
<P>
"The current estimated number of AIDS orphans is 300,000, and
it is projected to rise to 800,000 by year 2000," said
Muchinguri.
</P>
<P>
She stressed an HIV/AIDS prevention program would be placed at
the national and sub-national level.
</P>
<P>
"The Uganda trip showed us a lot, especially in the
involvement of politicians and government in the campaign against
AIDS," she said.
</P>
<P>
The minister was handed a citizens's petition calling on
government and politicians to fully commit to the campaign
against AIDS. 
</P>
</TEXT>
