<DOCNO> XIE19980725.0048 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mixed Reactions About Release of Rwanda Genocide </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, JULY 24 (Xinhua) -- The release of 136 genocide
suspects from Kigali Thursday has provoked mixed reactions in the
general public, with some people expressing fears that this could
provoke retribution from their victims.
</P>
<P>
"In releasing the suspects we targeted the terminally ill, the
old, as well as those whose files lack sufficiently convincing
evidence," the Kigali Prosecutor, Emmanuel Rukangira, told Rwanda
News Agency (RNA) Friday.
</P>
<P>
This process has been going on for quite a while and is going
to continue, he pointed out.
</P>
<P>
The announcement of the release broadcast on state-run radio
Rwandan radio and television Thursday night has triggered concern
about what might happen once those released reach their homes.
</P>
<P>
"Some of those set free could try to kill the evidence in
eliminating potential witnesses," one genocide survivor from
Nyamirambo told RNA.
</P>
<P>
This survivor affirmed that one of those released was a
militiaman who participated in the killings of the Tutsis in that
quarter of the capital in the 100-day genocide.
</P>
<P>
"I cannot understand how it is said that there is not enough
evidence for crimes he was charged with," the survivor said.
</P>
<P>
Other people in the capital Kigali fear that the victims would
tempted to take justice in their own hands, as the feel betrayed
by the judicial system in Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
But some organizations catering for survivors believe that
there is no problem with releasing genocide suspects who are
terminally sick, and who were just waiting for the end of their
life in prison.
</P>
<P>
"The pictures passed on television were quite shocking," a
chairperson of one of these organizations told RNA. "Those are
finished, they could not move by themselves, they were brought
out on stretchers..." he commented.
</P>
<P>
"As long as those allegedly without sufficiently incriminating
evidence, it is up to their communities to stand up and provide
it," he underscored.
</P>
<P>
He suggested that if those released presented a real menace to
the victims, the people should protest and have them punished.
</P>
<P>
In the past, people in southern Gikongoro Prefecture had shown
a staunch opposition against releasing the suspects, claiming
that some of them were involved in past pogroms which rocked the
area since 1959, before getting involved again in the 1994
killings.
</P>
<P>
In Butare Prefecture, more than 22 genocide suspects, who had
been reportedly released for lack of evidence, were murdered by
unknown people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
