<HEADLINE> Greece Slams Turkish President's Statement on Cyprus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, July 24 (Xinhua) -- Greece Friday expressed its
opposition to the statement made by Turkish President Suleyman
Demirel that Turkey would not allow Cyprus to become "a second
Crete."
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press briefing, Greek government spokesman
Dimitris Reppas described Demirel's statement as "highly
provocative," saying that it also revealed Ankara's "true
intentions."
</P>
<P>
The Turkish president reportedly said that Crete, an island in
the southern part of Greece, was given to Greece as a gift by
Turkey in the particular circumstances of the times, but this
could not be done in the case of Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Reppas urged neighboring Turkey to create suitable conditions
in the Bakan region rather than resorting to statements of the
type made by Demirel which created a climate of tension.
</P>
<P>
Greece and Turkey have been at odds for decades over their
disputes in the territorial waters, air space limits, the
delimitation of the continental shelf in the Aegean Sea and the
Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
Tensions between Greece and Turkey rose this year due to the
nearing of the deployment of Russian-made S-300 anti-aircraft
missiles in Cyprus, which has been divided into the Greek
Cypriots- dominated south and Turkish Cypriots-controlled north
since 1974 when Turkish troops landed and took over the northern
third of the island in the wake of a failed pro-Athens coup in
Nicosia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
