<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Outspoken French Lawyer Dies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, July 25 (Xinhua) -- Henri-Rene Garaud, a 72-year-old
French Lawyer known for American-style pragmatism and promotion of
the idea of self-defense, died in Paris on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
A founder of the Association of Legitimate Defense, Garaud is
known for anti-leftist views and his calls for the revival of the
death penalty in France, which was abolished in 1981.
</P>
<P>
He was also an advocate of absolute safety for private
properties.
</P>
<P>
Known as "the tenor of the bar," Garaud was a relentless
fighter in court and served as the lawyer for various clients
including small shop owners, jewellers, pump attendants, policemen
and other lower middle class people.
</P>
<P>
"See one who did you harm is punished, it's normal. When one
accepts a defense case, he should fight with all means for the
result," he once said.
</P>
<P>
By seeking patronization from ordinary people, Garaud said he
won success by climbing a watch tower not scaled until now.
</P>
<P>
"My cafe owners, pump attendants and jewellers are worth as
much as others," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
