<HEADLINE> Clinton Calls Capitol Shootout "Savagery" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 25 (Xinhua) -- With the Capitol's flags at
half-staff in mourning, U.S. President Bill Clinton Saturday
called a gunman's spree at the national landmark "a moment of
savagery at the front door of American civilization."
</P>
<P>
Speaking at Andrews Air Force base before leaving on a trip to
Norfolk, Virginia, Clinton praised the two police officers who
died in Friday's shootout and those who rushed to help.
</P>
<P>
"In this one heartless act, there were many acts of heroism,"
The Associated Press quoted Clinton as saying.
</P>
<P>
Investigators are trying to learn how and why a gunman burst
into the Capitol and opened fire before being shot and captured. A
female tourist was wounded in the exchange of gunfire.
</P>
<P>
The suspect, identified as Russell E. Weston Jr., 41, of rural
Rimini, Montana, was being held under heavy guard at a hospital
and was in critical condition Saturday after surgery for gunshot
wounds. Charges were pending.
</P>
<P>
With the Capitol reopened Saturday, Clinton said, "We must keep
it a place where people can freely and proudly walk the halls of
our government."
</P>
<P>
Killed were Jacob Chestnut, 58, and John Gibson, 42, both
18-year veterans of the Capitol police force. Each was married
with three children and colleagues said Chestnut, an Air Force
veteran, planned to retire soon.
</P>
<P>
The wounded tourist was identified as Angela Dickerson, 24.
George Washington University Hospital spokeswoman Lisa Saisselin
said Dickerson's condition had been upgraded from serious to
stable and she may be released Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Clinton praised the fallen officers for saving many others from
"exposure to lethal violence."
</P>
<P>
He also mentioned Republican Senator Bill Frist, a heart
surgeon, who rushed to the aid of the victims and the suspect.
</P>
<P>
"The shooting at the U.S. Capitol was a moment of savagery at
the front door of American civilization," Clinton said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
