<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SAARC Foreign Secretaries Continue Preparatory Work </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, July 25 (Xinhua) -- Foreign secretaries from the
seven-member South Asian Association for Regional Cooperation
(SAARC) began a two-day meeting here Saturday to review the
progress in implementing decisions made at last year's SAARC
summit in the Maldives.
</P>
<P>
They were discussing the whole range of items on the agenda for
the upcoming SAARC summit scheduled for July 29-31 in the Sri
Lankan capital, Pakistani Foreign Secretary Shamshad Ahmad told
Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
The foreign secretaries were meeting behind closed doors amid
tight security arrangements. A total of 6,000 police officers, in
addition to army soldiers, are being deployed in Colombo for the
summit.
</P>
<P>
Shamshad said the items they were reviewing included specific
projects now under consideration, the issues of preferential trade
and the proposed free trade zone in the region, various reports
from the SAARC's technical committees dealing with different areas
of cooperation within SAARC.
</P>
<P>
Progress in carrying out the anti-terrorism and anti-drugs
plans is also under discussion. Recommendations on the basis of
the discussions will be formulated for the SAARC foreign ministers
who will meet here on next Monday and Tuesday, he said.
</P>
<P>
Shamshad also said that the Group of Eminent Persons, set up at
the Male summit with the aim of developing a long-range vision and
formulating a perspective plan of action, will deliver its report
straight to the SAARC foreign ministers. "But they (the foreign
ministers) may ask us perhaps to look at it," he added.
</P>
<P>
At their summit in Male, the Maldives, in May last year, the
South Asian leaders decided to move faster from the South Asian
Preferential Trading Arrangement (SAPTA) to the South Asian Free
Trade Area (SAFTA), bringing forward the timetable for creating
such a free trade zone from 2005 to 2001.
</P>
<P>
SAARC, formed in 1985, groups Bangladesh, Bhutan, India,
Pakistan, the Maldives, Nepal and Sri Lanka. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980725.0061 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF Sees Robust Growth of Egypt's Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 25 (Xinhua) -- A Senior International Monetary Fund
(IMF) official said Saturday that Egyptian economy is growing
robustly and no longer needs IMF loans.
</P>
<P>
"The Egyptian economy can now stand alone. Egypt is no longer
in need of IMF support. But the fund will stand by ready for
providing any required technical assistance," IMF mission chief in
Cairo Howard Handy said.
</P>
<P>
The technical support will include outlining the bases of a
growing financial sector and means of promoting Egyptian
financial strategies. The IMF has been sending experts to help
governments seeking reform in economic areas.
</P>
<P>
Handy is in Egypt for the final review of an IMF loan
program. IMF approved a two-year, 350 million U.S. dollar loan to
Egypt in October 1996, but Cairo has not drawn on the money.
</P>
<P>
Egypt decided it wanted IMF technical support in macroeconomic
fields instead of cash.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the Middle East News Agency Saturday,
Handy said the IMF mission has been impressed by Egyptian
government's professionalism and commitment to continue the
IMF-sponsored reform program that started in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian Minister of Public Business Sector Atef Ebeid, on the
other hand, said Cairo is discussing "a new formula for future
cooperation" with the fund after the current economic reform
program ends in September.
</P>
<P>
Ebeid expects an agreement on that formula to be reached by
October, adding that Egypt does not need a new formal agreement
with the IMF but the fund will be ready to offer technical support.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian minister noted that Cairo is now preparaing for
"more ambitious future work" and seeking to make more progress on
the successes already achieved.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he underlined Cairo's commitment to privatization
and deregulation of the economy to maintain high growth rates.
</P>
<P>
The IMF made an assessment in May of Egyptian privatization
program, which indicated that Egypt ranked fourth on the list of
some 39 countries in terms of the efficiency in their
privatization drive. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
