<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Africa's Bank, Fund Support Road Project in E. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, July 25 (Xinhua) - The African Development Bank
(ADB) and the African Development Fund (ADF) have jointly pledged
19.8 billion Tanzanian Shillings (about 30 million U.S. Dollars) to
finance projects in the three member states of the East African
Cooperation (EAC).
</P>
<P>
The pledge was part of a cooperation agreement signed here
Thursday between visiting ADB President Omar Kabbaj and the
Executive Secretary of the EAC Secretariat Francis Muthaura,
local media reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Kabbaj said the ADB and ADF will support the 112-kilometer
Road Project which will link Kagera Region in Tanzania to the
road network in Uganda through Mtukula in a bid to promote
regional integration.
</P>
<P>
The two organizations will also finance other cooperation
projects on food security, agriculture and animal husbandry,
tourism, natural resources and environment, energy, transport and
communications.
</P>
<P>
Kabbaj, who concluded a two-day visit Thursday, hailed
the important positive political and economic changes which have
taken place over the past decade in the African continent.
</P>
<P>
Since the growth rate in the continent's GDP has risen from
the average of 1.6 percent between 1990 and 1994 to about three
percent in 1995, five percent in 1996 and 3.7 percent in 1997,
many countries have been experiencing economic recovery, he noted.
</P>
<P>
While underscoring the importance of collaboration between
the bank and the EAC secretariat, he said: "The deepening of
economic reforms and the progress made in stabilizing the
socio-political framework provides encouragement over the
region's economic development prospects."
</P>
<P>
The EAC was founded in 1996 on the basis of the defunct East
African Community which collapsed in 1977 due to reasons
including the divergence of economic policies then pursued by the
member states, the continued perception of disproportionate
sharing of benefits and lack of adequate compensation mechanisms.
</P>
<P>
Since then, the new EAC has been trying to address the
shortcomings inherent in the past cooperation initiatives and
determined to place the new regional integration on a sustainable
basis.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
