<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Waterlogged Wuhan Back on Track </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, July 25 (Xinhua) -- After suffering heavy urban flooding
from recent torrential rains, the city of Wuhan is returning to
normal as much of the rain water had been drained away by this
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
By 2:00 pm today, 100 million cubic meters of water had been
drained, and no large areas of flood water remained in this
capital of central China's Hubei Province.
</P>
<P>
Major thoroughfares have now reopened to traffic, and
two-thirds of the flood-stricken businesses have resumed
operation, including the eight large department stores that had
been closed by the flooding.
</P>
<P>
Local officials said the flood water in Wuhan was now basically
drained, but the 100,000 people who have been draining and
conducting rescue operation are still on high alert for another
possible siege of torrential rains.
</P>
<P>
Beginning early Tuesday morning, 34 hours of continuous heavy
rains brought 110 million cubic meters of water down on the
city.
</P>
<P>
By 2:00 pm today, the water level of the Yangtze River at Wuhan
reached 28.22 meters, or 0.92 meters above the danger mark.
</P>
<P>
The heaviest rainfall was 616.6 mm, a historic high.
</P>
<P>
In the last few days, a flood prevention contingent of 50,000
has been patrolling along the 287-kilometer-long Yangtze River dyke,
and no major breaks have been reported so far.
</P>
<P>
Prices at outdoor grocery markets rose only 20-50 percent,
an increase described by local people as within the normal range
for weather-related emergencies.
</P>
<P>
According to Wuhan's epidemic prevention department, there have
been no reports of epidemic outbreaks.
</P>
<P>
Latest forecasts warn that from July 27 to 29 torrential rains
are expected in the mainstream area of the lower reaches of the
Yangtze River and the Poyang Lake system. Hubei Province is now
experiencing the worst flooding since 1954.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
