<HEADLINE> Turkey's General Elections Fall in April 1999 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, July 25 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Prime Minister Mesut
Yilmaz said Saturday that he and his coalition partners have
bridged gaps and agreed to general elections April next year, the
semi-official Anatolia News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Yilmaz, Democratic Left Party (DS) Chairman Bulent Ecevit and
Democratic Turkey Party (DTP) leader Husammatin Cindoruk reached
agreement during their discussions in Istanbul, the largest city
of Turkey, Saturday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement endorsed by the three partners, the general
elections will be held across the country on April 25, 1999.
</P>
<P>
His coalition partner, Ecevit, had held that the elections
should be held in November or December of this year.
</P>
<P>
Another partner, Cindoruk, had strongly opposed the elections
taking place either in the fall or in April 1999, and requested
that a later date be fixed.
</P>
<P>
Having reached consensus with Republican People's Party (CHP)
leader Deniz Baykal, who provides support to Yilmaz's minority
coalition government from outside, Yilmaz wanted the elections to
be held in April 1999.
</P>
<P>
According to the Yilmaz-Baykal agreement, both the provincial
and general elections will be held together in April.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, in line with Baykal's request, Yilmaz's coalition
will resign at the end of this year and a "low profile election
government" will be formed.
</P>
<P>
But Ecevit opposed the idea of an election government, saying
this concept would cause loss of valuable time and adversely
affect the completion of reforms initiated by the coalition.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
