<HEADLINE> Yangtze Water Level Reaches Record High In Jiujiang </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANCHANG, July 25 (Xinhua) -- The water level of the Yangtze
River climbed above the historic high today at its Jiujiang
section in east China's Jiangxi Province, topping the previous
record by 0.04 m to reach 22.4 m at 8:00 pm.
</P>
<P>
The previous high was recorded in 1995.
</P>
<P>
"It's the second time the water level has exceeded the record
this year," Acting Mayor Liu Jifu told Xinhua, referring to the
22.2 m recorded on July 4.
</P>
<P>
The water level of Poyang Lake has topped 21.75 m, 2.75 m
higher than the danger line, and is approaching the record high of
21.93 m, according to local reports.
</P>
<P>
Local weathermen say that more heavy rains are expected to
arrive in the province in the next few days, forecasting that
water levels of both the Yangtze River and the Poyang Lake will
rise further still.
</P>
<P>
To help Jiangxi fight against the possibility of severe
flooding, central and local governments are sending more relief
supplies to flood-threatened areas.
</P>
<P>
Some 900,000 people have been stationed on local dykes to
prevent any possible breaches.
</P>
<P>
"We are making every effort to safeguard the dykes of the
Yangtze, the urban districts of Jiujiang city, as well as key
water conservancy facilities along the Beijing-Kowloon railway,"
said Jiangxi Governor Shu Shengyou.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
