<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nuke Tests Thwart Progress of SAARC: Chairman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, July 25 (Xinhua) -- Nuclear tests by India and
Pakistan have done much to thwart progress of the South Asian
Association for Regional Cooperation (SAARC), Chairman of the
Press Council of India P. B. Sawant said here Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Opening a conference on "An Initiative for the Confederation of
SAARC Countries" organized by SAARC Citizen Forum, Sawant said the
nuclear tests have further strained the tenuous bond between SAARC
member countries.
</P>
<P>
"The tests have put the clock of the progress of the
organization (SAARC) back by many years," Sawant said in his
opening address.
</P>
<P>
Heads of states or government of the SAARC countries are
scheduled to hold a summit in Colombo towards the end of this
month to discuss, among others, regional cooperations between
South Asian countries.
</P>
<P>
"While on the one hand, we have been talking of regional
cooperation and pooling of resources for common development, here
we are expending our meager resources on destructive activities,"
Sawant said.
</P>
<P>
In such circumstances, he said, to talk of common economic,
social, cultural, and technological development sounds a big joke.
</P>
<P>
In the present political scenario, the goal of confederation
might be laudable but seems to be distant cry, Sawant said, adding
that "we may not be able to march towards it, but we can at least
inch towards it."
</P>
<P>
SAARC, established in December 1985 with an aim to promote
economic, social, cultural, scientific and technological
cooperations in South Asian region, is composed of Bangladesh,
Bhutan, India, Maldives, Nepal, Pakistan and Sri Lanka. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
