<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yeltsin Reaffirms Support for Chechnya President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 25 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin has
reaffirmed support for the presidency of Aslan Maskhadov in
Russia's breakaway republic of Chechnya, and demanded talks to
ensure law and order in the volatile region.
</P>
<P>
In a meeting Saturday with Prime Minister Sergei Kiriyenko in
Shuiskaya Chupa, where the president is recessing, Yeltsin called
for a Kiriyenko-Maskhadov meeting for measures to ensure stability
and law in Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
"I reaffirm once again that we support the government of
Chechnya and Aslan Maskhadov personally," Yeltsin said. "If
someone has any doubt about that, he is wrong."
</P>
<P>
"If Maskhadov wants the meeting to be held we shall arrange
it," Itar-Tass quoted Yeltsin as saying.
</P>
<P>
Kiriyenko said a meeting with Maskhadov was designed to
thoroughly discuss the Chechnya situation and measures to ensure
normal law and order in the region without violating either
Russian or Chechen legislations.
</P>
<P>
Maskhadov escaped an assassination attempt with some bruises
Thursday when a parked car exploded just as his motorcade was
passing by.
</P>
<P>
Two of his bodyguards were killed and three others seriously
wounded in the blast.
</P>
<P>
Maskhadov, viewed as the most moderate leader in Chechnya,
which is seeking independence from Russia, had first accused the
Russian secret service and then other military factions in
Chechnya of masterminding the plot.
</P>
<P>
Tension has been running high in Chechnya, and Maskhadov
declared a state of emergency more than a month ago to crack down
on rampant crime and violence.
</P>
<P>
Chechnya has witnessed rising internal strife between rival
factions following the departure of Russian troops in late 1996.
</P>
<P>
Under an agreement reached earlier that year between Maskhadov
and Alexandr Lebed, then national security advisor to Yeltsin, a
decision on Chechnya's status would be postponed until 2001.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
