<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indian PM Looking Forward to Meeting Sharif </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, July 25 (Xinhua) -- Indian Prime Minister Atal
Bihari Vajpayee said Saturday he was looking forward to meeting
Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif with a positive mind and
sincerity.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the Week Magazine on the eve of his
departure for Colombo to attend the summit of the South Asian
Association for Regional Cooperation (SAARC), Vajpayee expressed
his hope that the scheduled meeting with Sharif would result in a
forward movement in relations with neighboring Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
He said he wished to discuss differences between India and
Pakistan including those on Kashmir bilaterally.
</P>
<P>
The Indian Prime minister, however, ruled out a third party
mediation on the Kashmir issue, saying that "we are of the firm
view that there is no role for any third party in our bilateral
relationship."
</P>
<P>
Vajpayee is scheduled to hold his meeting with Sharif, the
first between the two prime ministers since the nuclear tests by
India and Pakistan in May, on the sidelines of the SAARC summit on
July 29.
</P>
<P>
He said that India likes to work with Pakistan so as to enhance
the confidence-building measures.
</P>
<P>
"In the aftermath of our nuclear tests, we are also prepared to
discuss a no-first-use of nuclear weapon agreement with Pakistan,"
said Vajpayee.
</P>
<P>
He declared that India was committed to resolving its
differences with Pakistan peacefully and through a process of
bilateral dialogue so as to build a stable structure of
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Asked whether New Delhi would sign the Comprehensive Test Ban
Treaty (CTBT) if Pakistan were to do so, the prime minister said
as far as India was concerned, there is no link with Pakistan in
signing the CTBT as India's decision would based on its national
interests.  
</P>
</TEXT>
