<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. to Judge First Rwandan Criminal in August </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, July 25 (Xinhua) -- Agwu Ukiwe Okali, registrar
of the International Criminal Tribunal for Rwanda (ICTR) has said
that the tribunal's first judgement was expected in August in the
case of Jean-Paul Akayesu, an ICTR press release reported
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
While visiting Kigali, capital of Rwanda, Okali said besides
the case of Akayesu, the former bourg mestre of Taba Commune in
Gitarama Prefecture, the tribunal also expects to deliver its
sentence on Jean Kambanda, former Prime Minister of Rwanda at the
end of August.
</P>
<P>
Kambanda is the first Rwandan suspect who pleaded guilty
to genocide and crimes against humanity before the tribunal based
in Arusha, northern Tanzania, on May 1 this year.
</P>
<P>
During his meeting with Okali Friday, Rwandan Vice-President
and Minister of Defense Paul Kagame said the
tribunal has made significant progress in its work under
difficult circumstances.
</P>
<P>
His government pledged strong support for the Tribunal's
process, because "we are partners in this situation".
</P>
<P>
Okali has been on a week-long working visit to Rwanda since
Monday. He has met with senior officials of the Rwandan
government, the media, and representatives of civil society
including the victims of the 1994 genocide.
</P>
<P>
A total of 35 suspects have been indicted so far by the ICTR,
founded by the United Nations following the Rwanda massacre in
April 1994 soon after President Juvenal Habyarimana, a Hutu, died
when his plane was shot down over capital Kigali.
</P>
<P>
Over 500,000 people, mostly Tutsis and moderate Hutus, were
reportedly killed in the three-month slaughter.  
</P>
</TEXT>
