<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jiangsu on Flood Alert </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, July 25 (Xinhua) -- The water level on the Jiangsu
section of the Yangtze River in east China has risen rapidly this
week due to flooding in the river's middle and upper reaches.
</P>
<P>
The water flow of the Yangtze -- 60,000 to over 70,000
cu. m. per second -- has topped the warning mark for a month since
mid June, and the protective capability of the dykes along the
river has declined.
</P>
<P>
The water flow reached 77,200 cubic meters per second today,
according to a report issued by the Provincial Flood Control
Headquarters. The water level in Xiaguan, in the provincial
capital of Nanjing, has reached 9.82 meters, 1.32 meters higher
than the danger level, and water levels on other parts of the
Yangtze have also reached record highs.
</P>
<P>
The situation will become more severe when flood peaks from
the middle and upper reaches of the river approach.
</P>
<P>
As many as 340,000 people have been mobilized around the clock
to protect the dykes, said Xu Junren, deputy director of the
provincial water resources department.  
</P>
</TEXT>
