<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Malaysia's Property Market Worst Hit, But </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, July 25 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia's property sector,
engulfed by the regional economic turmoil, has been hit the
hardest, but is not all gloom and doom. This is the general view
of the Speakers at the 10th National Real Estate Convention here
on July 22-23.
</P>
<P>
Following the economic slowdown since July last year, property
prices on the local market have gone down between 20 and 35
percent, depending on the location.
</P>
<P>
There is about 38 billion ringgit (about 9.22 billion U.S.
dollars) worth of property "lying around" in Malaysia now.
</P>
<P>
The credit crunch, high interest rates, over-supply of high-end
commercial and residential units, lack of confidence and a
wait-and-see attitude among purchasers have all contributed to the
overall gloom of the property market.
</P>
<P>
Despite the gloomy scene in the property sector at present,
most speakers at the convention were optimistic that the sector
would recover.
</P>
<P>
Housing Developers' Association President Eddy Chen Lo Loi said
the property sector has reached the near bottom and will soon be
on its road to recovery.
</P>
<P>
And Jeffrey Ng, Managing Director of Asia Pacific Land Bhd,
said despite of the present glut in the Malaysian property market,
developers can still benefit from some of the downturn's positive
effects such as the declining labor costs that now allows
developers to choose the best employees at a lower pay rate.
</P>
<P>
It was also noted that demand for housing will still continue
as there will always be population growth in the country.
</P>
<P>
With the country's population projected to touch 23.3 million
by the end of this century, the requirement for housing to meet
the needs of the growing population is tremendous.
</P>
<P>
Housing, a major industry which attracts considerable resources
and generated employment opportunities, accounted for 10 percent
of a gross domestic product (GDP) of 170 billion ringgit (about
41.262 billion U.S. dollars at present rate) and for 40 to 50
percent of some 850,000 employed by the construction sector in
1996 when there were about 4.8 million housing units catering to a
population of about 20 million people.
</P>
<P>
According to Henry Butcher Lim and Long Director Fahariah Abdul
Wahab, the market for houses below 150,000 ringgit (about 36,407
U.S. dollars) was expected to grow despite of the current economic
situation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980725.0086 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Malaysia's Property Market Worst Hit, But </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
As Alan Tong Kok Mau, President of FIABCI, the International
Real Estate Federation, said some developers have survived the
economic crisis successfully as the demand continued to be there.
"Slackening demand does not mean there is no demand ... so we have
to sharpen on skills to find niches in the market."
</P>
<P>
As for ways to tackle the current problems faced by developers,
it was proposed that a serious study be made on the Real Estates
Investment Trusts (REITS), a U.S. model, as instruments to create
liquidity in the real estate market.
</P>
<P>
Also, to encourage purchasers to invest in the housing market,
it was suggested that support be given to the first-time house
buyers such as exemptions from all monetary curbs on housing loans
or having preferential rates of interest.
</P>
<P>
Besides, it was also proposed that the quantum for withdrawal
for housing under the Employee Provident Fund (EPF) be increased
to reduce the burden on eligible purchasers, because the amount of
housing loans available from banks has decreased and the interest
charged by banks on housing loans is high.
</P>
<P>
As a measure to attract more foreign buyers into Malaysia's
property sector, the approval process for foreign purchase of
properties was proposed to be limited to a single stage or the
state authorities.
</P>
<P>
Presently, foreigners who want to purchase properties worth
more than 250,000 ringgit (about 60,679 U.S. dollars) in Malaysia
must gain government's approval in two stages -- firstly, from the
Foreign Investment Committee (FIC) and secondly, the state
authorities.
</P>
<P>
As such, the government has been called for the setting up of a
consultative mechanism together with the private sector to
formulate guidelines and rules on property purchased by
foreigners.
</P>
<P>
It was also suggested that tax incentives be offered and
restrictions on purchases by foreigners be relaxed to woo foreign
participation in the local property market, which could bring the
much needed foreign exchange, help create more employment and
subsequently stimulate the property market and related downstream
industries.
</P>
<P>
The government has been responsive and ready to revitalize the
industry with the measures introduced including the lifting of
levies imposed on foreign purchases of properties and granting of
loans to properties costing 150,000 ringgit (about 36,407 U.S.
dollars) or less besides setting up the National Housing Fund.
</P>
<P>
More recently, under the National Economic Recovery Plan
announced on July 23, the property sector is recommended to be
reclassified from "unproductive" to "priority" for bank loans.
</P>
<P>
A general view is that the property market turnaround depends
on the country's economic recovery. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
