<HEADLINE> East China Province Steps Up Anti-Flood Efforts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANCHANG, July 25 (Xinhua) -- Water levels of major rivers in
east China's Jiangxi Province have surpassed the danger line and
are approaching the historic highs from continuous heavy rains in
the province since July 17, according to local official sources.
</P>
<P>
The water level of the Yangtze River at the Jiujiang Measuring
Station was 22.1 m at 8:00 a,m, today, 2.6 m above the danger line
and only 0.1 m lower than the record high.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the water level of Boyang Lake at the Hukou
Measuring Station stood at 21.63 m, 2.63 m over the danger line.
</P>
<P>
Major reservoirs have opened their gates to discharge flood
waters, sources say.
</P>
<P>
Local people have stepped up their efforts to safeguard the
dykes of the Jiangxi section of the Yangtze River, the Poyang Lake,
and some local rivers and reservoirs.
</P>
<P>
Landslides caused by the heavy waters have killed one person
and injured two others. Vast areas of farmland have also been
devastated by the flood waters.
</P>
<P>
In Nanchang city, the provincial capital, major thoroughfares
were submerged in water on July 24, blocking traffic in some parts
of the city.  
</P>
</TEXT>
