<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Palestinians Ready to Continue Talks With Israel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 25 (Xinhua) -- The Palestinian leadership was
ready to continue direct talks with Israel in a bid to clinch a
deal over Israeli withdrawal, the Voice of Palestine radio
reported on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued after Friday night's Cabinet meeting, the
Palestinian National Authority (PNA) declared its willingness to
continue the talks, which were resumed last week.
</P>
<P>
The statement blamed the deadlock in the Israeli-Palestinian
peace process on the hard-line policies adopted by the Israeli
government.
</P>
<P>
However, the statement said, the Palestinians were willing to
continue talks in order to avoid a outbreak of widespread violence
in the region.
</P>
<P>
The talks on an long overdue deal on Israeli troop withdrawal
from the West Bank hit a snag Wednesday after three days of talks.
</P>
<P>
The PNA refused to continue the talks to protest against what
they called Israeli refusal to accept the United States proposal
on the scope of the withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. proposal asked Israel to hand over 13 percent more of
the West Bank to the Palestinians during the second stage of
redeployment.
</P>
<P>
But after his meeting with Israeli Public Security Minister
Avigdor Kahalani Friday in Ramallah, PNA President Yasser Arafat
changed his position and agreed to resume talks.
</P>
<P>
The right-wing in the Israeli government said the proposed
scope was unacceptable, citing that it would endanger the
security of the Jewish country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
