<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: ASEAN Stresses Unity in Face of Economic Woes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 25 (Xinhua) -- The 31st ASEAN Ministerial Meeting
(AMM), which ended here Saturday afternoon, stressed the need for
ASEAN member countries to unite and cooperate more closely to
resolve the financial crisis that has ravaged the regional
economies since July last year.
</P>
<P>
In their joint statement and in their speeches at the two-day
meeting, the delegates made it clear that only unity and
cooperation can help their countries tide over the economic
difficulties and return their economies to the prosperity they had
previously enjoyed.
</P>
<P>
Philippine President Joseph Estrada, presiding over the opening
ceremony, pointed out, "As we have gone through this storm
together, we have acquired a deeper realization that we need to
bind ourselves to one another even more tightly."
</P>
<P>
The Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) groups
Brunei, Indonesia, Laos, Malaysia, Myanmar, the Philippines,
Singapore, Thailand and Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
Some ASEAN countries, particularly Indonesia and Thailand, have
been hit hard by the financial crisis: their currencies have
fallen by as much as up to 80 percent against the U.S. dollar,
banks and factories closed down and millions of people have been
thrown out of work. Some members have even registered negative
economic growth, presenting a sharp contrast to the fact that the
region was one of the fastest-growing areas in the world before
the crisis struck.
</P>
<P>
In his closing statement Saturday afternoon, Philippine
Secretary of Foreign Affairs Domingo Siazon, whose country is
chairman of this year's AMM meetings, noted that in face of the
difficulties, the ASEAN, instead of bowing to the pressures,
"sought to enhance its solidarity and cooperation."
</P>
<P>
Foreign ministers from other member countries also called for
closer unity and cooperation in reviving the economies in the
region.
</P>
<P>
"If we have faith in our shared vision, if we use our resources
with foresight and wisdom and help one another in an unrelenting
pursuit of development, we will not only survive, we will not
merely recover -- we will... triumph over our adversities and
resume our steady march toward stable peace and sustained
progress," said Indonesian Foreign Minister Ali Alatas, whose
country is among the hardest hit in the crisis, at the opening
session.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Minister Surin Pitsuwan of Thailand, where the
financial crisis first erupted, said, "During this crucial
juncture, it is... vital for us... to redouble our efforts to
strengthen cohesiveness and cooperation."
</P>
<P>
"The way forward remains cooperation, more cooperation and
better cooperation," Malaysian Foreign Minister Abdullah Badawi
declared at the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Minister Somsavat Lengsavad of Laos, which joined the
ASEAN just last year, noted in his statement that in face of the
economic difficulties, "our member states have intensified greater
cooperation and coordination to address the current situation."
</P>
<P>
"Closer cooperation will help us overcome the current crisis,
continue to advance on the path toward prosperity," Vietnamese
Foreign Minister Nguyen Manh Cam told the meeting.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN has actually already adopted a number of collective
measures to address the economic problems and mitigate the effects
on the people.
</P>
<P>
Among them is a decision by ASEAN finance ministers to
establish an ASEAN surveillance mechanism to closely monitor
regional macroeconomic and financial indicators and to serve as an
early warning system and thus help avert a recurrence of the
crisis. Work is now under way to implement the decision, which was
"strongly endorsed" by the foreign ministers at their meeting.
</P>
<P>
The finance ministers have also endorsed the use of ASEAN
currencies for the settlement of intra-ASEAN trade to reduce
members' dependency on the U.S. dollar and promote intra-ASEAN
trade. Modalities for carrying this out are to be agreed upon
between the trading partners concerned and are being worked out
between Malaysia and the Philippines, Malaysia and Indonesia,
Malaysia and Thailand, and Indonesia and Thailand, ASEAN
Secretary-General Rodolfo Severino said in a report to the AMM.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN member countries have also agreed to speed up the
implementation of the ASEAN Free Trade Area, the ASEAN Investment
Area and the ASEAN Industrial Cooperation Scheme to promote trade
and investment and maintain an open trade and investment
environment in ASEAN. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980725.0093 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ethiopian Bank Makes More Profit in 1997/98 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, July 25 (Xinhua) -- The Commercial Bank of
Ethiopia made a profit of over 76.86 million U.S. Dollars during
the just-ended 1997/98 fiscal year, 10.7 percent over the target
of 69.4 million U.S. Dollars.
</P>
<P>
Habte-Sellasie Hagos, Vice-President of marketing and planning
sector of the bank has said that the good performance of the bank
was the result of the country's overall economic growth,
considerable boost of the private economic sector as well as the
expansion of trade, the Ethiopian Herald reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Habte-Sellasie said the bank has also given out short, medium
and long-term loans amounting to 514 million U.S. Dollars during
the fiscal year, 10.6 percent and 28.9 percent more than those
loaned during 1996/97 and 1995/96 respectively.
</P>
<P>
He contributed the increase of loans to the introduction of
new loaning systems which provide wider opportunities for
starting new projects.
</P>
<P>
The Commercial Bank of Ethiopia is the largest bank in the
country with 168 branches. 
</P>
</TEXT>
