<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> hke072533-ASEAN Nations Sign Joint Declaration for Drug-Free ASEAN </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 25 (Xinhua) -- Foreign ministers of the
Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) signed here
Saturday a joint declaration which aims to make the region free
from drug production, abuse and trafficking by the year 2020.
</P>
<P>
The document, the Joint Declaration for a Drug-Free ASEAN, is
part of ASEAN's programs for closer coordination in building
Southeast Asia into a region free from the drug menace.
</P>
<P>
The move was taken by ASEAN in the realization that the growing
drug menace could seriously endanger development programs of ASEAN
member countries, especially in relation to the region's youth and
the preservation of the moral fabric of the family as the basic
unit of society.
</P>
<P>
The ASEAN member countries have expressed fears that the
illicit drug trade, which is inextricably linked to other
transnational crimes including money laundering and arms
smuggling, could escalate to such a level that it is posing
"serious political and security threats" to the region.
</P>
<P>
The declaration seeks all modalities to eradicate illicit drug
production, processing, trafficking and use in ASEAN by the year
2020.
</P>
<P>
It called for ASEAN countries to cooperate with non-ASEAN
nations and international agencies in the fight against drug, pass
stricter laws on drug abuse and trafficking, expand awareness,
education and rehabilitation programs among the youth, and
strengthen human resources training in the fields of law
enforcement, treatment and rehabilitation and research.
</P>
<P>
The treaty also urged the ASEAN members to intensify the
exchange of information among themselves, cooperate and coordinate
in the areas of investigation, prosecution and research, and
enhance the roles of non-governmental organizations as well as the
private sector.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN groups Brunei, Indonesia, Laos, Malaysia, Myanmar, the
Philippines, Singapore, Thailand and Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
The ministers signed the joint declaration on the occasion of
the 31st ASEAN Ministerial Meeting which opened Friday and closed
Saturday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980725.0095 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chongqing Strengthens Anti-smuggling Efforts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHONGQING, July 25 (Xinhua) -- The city of Chongqing in
southwest China will strengthen its crackdown on smuggling, a
municipal government official said today.
</P>
<P>
As the biggest city in southwest China, Chongqing is a traffic
hub of the upper reaches of the Yangtze River, China's
longest. Smuggling has become rampant in the region in recent
years, with illicit trafficking in cultural relics, petroleum,
automobiles, and electrical appliances.
</P>
<P>
The city's Customs office made arrests in dozens of smuggling
cases, each involving more than 300,000 yuan (about 36,000 U.S.
dollars) worth of goods, and seized more than 160 cultural relics
last year.
</P>
<P>
The city government has called on various departments to crack
a number of major smuggling cases and deal severely with the
smugglers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
