<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> hke072529 -Chinese Ambassador to India on China's S. Asia Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, July 25 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Ambassador to India Zhou
Gang said Saturday that it is China's consistent policy to develop
neighborly and friendly relations and mutually beneficial
cooperation with the South Asian countries.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a seminar on "Sino-Indian Relations" organized by
the Indian International Center here, Zhou Gang said that the
South Asian countries are close neighbors of China and traditional
friendship has long existed between the Chinese people and the
people of these countries.
</P>
<P>
"China not only wants to develop with them long-term and stable
relations of neighborliness and friendship towards the 21st
century, but also hopes that they will treat one another on an
equal footing, live in harmony, develop friendly cooperation, seek
common ground while reserving differences, promote mutual
understanding and mutual accommodation and settle their
differences and disputes through peaceful means," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Promoting friendly relations between China and the South Asian
countries is conducive to peace, stability and development in
South Asia, and conforms to fundamental interests of the Chinese
people and the people of these countries," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
Referring to Sino-Indian relations, he first of all recalled
friendly exchanges and traditional friendship between the two
countries in the past over 2,000 years.
</P>
<P>
He said from 1988 to 1996 there had been constant top level
exchanges of visits by the leaders of the two countries. The state
visit to India by Chinese President Jiang Zemin in November 1996
in particular is an important historical event in the two
countries' bilateral relations and has pushed them onto a new
phase of development at the turn of this century.
</P>
<P>
"During the visit the leaders of the two countries agreed to
establish the constructive and cooperative partnership towards the
21st century on the basis of the Five Principles of Peaceful
Coexistence," he said.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that since April and May this year the
Sino-Indian relations have witnessed abnormal developments and
"this is something we are unwilling to see."
</P>
<P>
"The so-called China's threat to India's security is baseless.
Fictitious charges against China have greatly hurt the feelings of
the Chinese people and harmed the Sino-Indian relations," he
emphasized.
</P>
<P>
"China does not pose any threat to India. The Chinese side
could not but refute some wanton attack and accusation against
China by certain personages in India in order to safeguard the
friendly relations between our two countries and bring the
Sino-Indian relations back onto the track of healthy development
at an early date," he said.
</P>
<P>
"What China hopes from India is neighborliness, friendship and
cooperation. What China wishes India is stability, progress and
development," he further said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
