<DOCNO> XIE19980725.0099 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-25 12:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Khatami Vows to Give Freedom to People </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, July 25 (Xinhua) -- Iranian President Mohammad Khatami
vowed here Saturday to give freedom to the people, saying freedom
was a "divine right of human beings."
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the opening session of the 17th meeting of
heads of education departments from across the country, Khatami
stressed the existing obstacles to the achievement of freedom
and administration of justice should be removed.
</P>
<P>
A religion which respects man must first respect man's freedom,
the official news agency IRNA quoted him as saying.
</P>
<P>
If the religion stands against freedom in that society, then
freedom will be suppressed, he added.
</P>
<P>
In a veiled attack against the hard-liners in the country,
Khatami denounced them for suppressing freedom and "trying to pit
the religion against freedom by manipulating people's feelings."
</P>
<P>
A group of senior clerics from the Mom seminary on
Wednesday called on Khatami to curb the budding freedom in the
country, in the press in particular. They highlighted the
importance of strengthening spiritual values in the society.
</P>
<P>
Some prominent conservative figures recently also accused the
Khatami's moderate government of pursuing western-style freedom
under the title of political reforms.
</P>
<P>
However, Khatami called on the people not to allow those
hard-liners to dictate to the society, "because it is like
insulting the personality of human beings."
</P>
<P>
In an Islamic system of government, the framework of which
has been determined by law, no one has the right to impose
his views on the society as an absolute right, he said.
</P>
<P>
The president also noted that freedom and law were
indispensable, saying that without law, the society would be in a
state of chaos. 
</P>
</TEXT>
