<HEADLINE> Yemeni FM in Saudi Arabia for Talks on Clashes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, July 25 (Xinhua) -- Yemeni Foreign Minister Abdul
Qader Ba-Jammal Saturday arrived in Jeddah, Saudi Arabia, for
talks with Saudi officials on last week's clashes on an island,
the Kuwait News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Informed sources said that Ba-Jammal was expected to meet Saudi
Crown Prince Abdullah Ibn Abdul-Aziz and Foreign Minister Prince
Saud Al-Faisal.
</P>
<P>
They would try to reach a compromise calling for preventing
further bloodshed between the two countries through the
demarcation of their disputed borders, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Ba-Jammal was initially scheduled to visit the kingdom last
Tuesday or Wednesday, but postponed due to domestic affairs.
</P>
<P>
Both Yemen and Saudi Arabia have confirmed that armed clashes
took place last Sunday on the Duwaima Island, over which both
sides have claimed sovereignty. Three Yemeni soldiers were killed
and an officer captured in the clashes with Saudi troops.
</P>
<P>
Yemeni President Ali Abdullah Saleh accused Saudi Arabia last
Monday of occupying the island. Meanwhile, Saudi Interior Minister
Prince Nayef Bin Abdul-Aziz blamed the Yemeni troops for initiating
the conflict by firing at the Saudi positions on the island.
</P>
<P>
But Nayef said on Wednesday that since both countries agreed
to hold talks on the dispute, tensions on the island had been
defused and the situation there remained calm.
</P>
<P>
The recent clashes were the most serious since 1995 when Saudi
Arabia and Yemen signed a memorandum of understanding, calling for
the establishment of joint committees to demarcate the borders.
</P>
</TEXT>
