<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Famine Looms Large in S. Somalia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, July 25 (Xinhua) -- There is a growing fear that a
large scale famine may strike again in southern Somalia and the
three regions of Bay, Bakol and Gedo in particular.
</P>
<P>
Despite the humanitarian effort by the World Food Program, the
regions of Bay and Bakol are suffering severe food shortage
following the lack of enough rains in the Gu' season this year.
</P>
<P>
According to Ahmed Sheikh Hamud, the district commissioner of
Bardale Town, 55 km west of Baidoa, the evidence of serious
famine can be seen in the streets where the children with swollen
face and inflated abdomen for marasmus are barely leaning against
the walls of their huts rather than playing in happiness.
</P>
<P>
The region, the highest sorghum producing area in the country,
is now having no single farm following the floods of late last
year which washed away the underground food reservoirs and
displaced farmers.
</P>
<P>
Hamud said the famine is also affecting the livestock where
the camels, the most resistant animal, and goats are dying at the
rate of two or three per day for each family.
</P>
<P>
Aden Ibrahim Finni, the district commissioner of Wajid, 90 km
north of Baidoa, said that apart
from the famine which has so far claimed the lives of more than
15, the people are also dying of malaria.
</P>
<P>
" Twelve people have died in the past week of the disease alone
and there is no medicine," said Finni.
</P>
<P>
In the border region of Gedo where a large reconciliatory
meeting is still going on between the Somali National Front (SNF)
faction and the Islamic fundamentalist group of Al-Itihad
Al-Islam, the famine is still tightening its grip on the
civilians already badly affected by the civil strive.
</P>
<P>
Ali Mohamed Mukhtar, the Deputy Chairman of SNF, said three
children have died of famine in Bur Dhubo village early in the
week.
</P>
<P>
Mukhtar has made an appeal to the U.N. and international aid
agencies to help the people in the region and encourage the
on-going peace meeting which is to be concluded later in the
month or early next month.
</P>
<P>
The famine in these regions is also felt in Mogadishu as
dozens of families are reaching the capital per day in search of
better living and food from the few refugee camps still open for
the internally displaced people.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of women and children have joined the already
innumerable street beggars in the capital since the beginning of
the month, while poorly dressed middle aged men are begging
inside the mosques for help. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980725.0108 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zhuhai City Official Faces Bribery Charges </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHUHAI, July 25 (Xinhua) -- Li Guoqin, former director of the
state assets administration of Zhuhai, an special economic zone
and a coastal open city bordering Macao in south China's Guangdong
Province, has been arrested by the city's procuratorial office and
charged with receiving bribes.
</P>
<P>
The 54-year-old Li was charged with having taken bribes worth more
than 200,000 yuan (24,000 U.S dollars).
</P>
<P>
Li was also charged with misappropriating a large amount of
public funds. More than 70 million yuan (8.4 million US dollars)
in public funds were diverted by Li to privately-owned
corporations from 1992 to 1997, during which time he allegedly
took bribes totaling some 170,000 yuan (20,500 US dollars) and
more than 50,000 Hong Kong dollars (6,460 U.S. dollars). Most of
these public funds have not yet been recovered.
</P>
<P>
The investigation of Li's case has been concluded and he will
soon face trial.  
</P>
</TEXT>
