<HEADLINE> Future of Sheraton Kampala Hotel Remains </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, July 25 (Xinhua) -- The Ethiopian buyer of Sheraton
Kampala Hotel has not yet paid the balance of 17 million U.S.
Dollars for the price, making the future of the Number one hotel
here uncertain.
</P>
<P>
The deadline for the payment expires next Monday, the New
Vision daily reported Saturaday,
</P>
<P>
The Ethiopian-based Midroc bought the hotel for 19 million
dollars and it made a cash bond deposit of two million dollars.
</P>
<P>
"I really don't know what is happening to them. I also tried
to call Mr. Alfred Ireland in Addis but I couldn't find him,"
Leonard Muganwa, the Executive Director of Uganda's Enterprise
Development Project, was quoted as saying Friday.
</P>
<P>
"Though they still have up to Monday to meet the deadline, it
is also still tricky because cash transfers cannot be made on a
Sunday," he added.
</P>
<P>
When asked about what would happen if the buyer could not pay
the balance on time, Muganwa said he wouldn't wish that to happen
and it would mean the agreement has collapsed. But he did not
elaborate.
</P>
<P>
Midroc, owned by a Saudi Abrabian, millionaire Muhammad
Al-Amoudi, had requested for extension of the deadline. 
</P>
</TEXT>
