<HEADLINE> ASEAN Issues Joint Communique at End of Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 25 (Xinhua) -- Foreign ministers of the
Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) issued a joint
communique here Saturday afternoon, in which they welcomed the
signing of a protocol allowing outside countries to join the
Treaty of Amity and Cooperation in Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
Issued at the end of the two-day 31st ASEAN Ministerial Meeting
(AMM), the joint communique said the foreign ministers from the
nine member countries "had an extensive exchange of views on
current regional and international developments."
</P>
<P>
They discussed the measures taken by ASEAN and its member
countries to address the current financial situation.
</P>
<P>
"The foreign ministers noted the efforts being undertaken at
the national and regional levels to address the regional economic
crisis," the communique said.
</P>
<P>
They "strongly endorsed" the decision made by the ASEAN finance
ministers to establish an ASEAN surveillance mechanism to closely
monitor regional macroeconomic and financial indicators and to
serve as an early warning system and welcomed ASEAN finance
ministers' decision to support the use of regional currencies for
promoting intra-ASEAN trade and the use of bilateral payments
arrangements on a voluntary basis between individual ASEAN
countries.
</P>
<P>
In the communique, the ministers also expressed welcome to the
signing of the Second Protocol to the Treaty of Amity and
Cooperation in Southeast Asia (TAC).
</P>
<P>
Under the protocol, non-Southeast Asian states will be able to
accede to the TAC "as an instrument of commitment to friendly and
constructive relations with countries of Southeast Asia."
</P>
<P>
"The foreign ministers urged non-Southeast Asian states,
especially the major powers, to accede to the TAC," which was
signed in 1976, the communique said.
</P>
<P>
In the communique, the ministers expressed satisfaction with
"the good progress" made by the ASEAN Regional Forum (ARF) and
renewed ASEAN's commitment "to be the primary driving force of the
ARF and to ensure the continued development of the ARF as an
effective forum in promoting security dialogue and cooperation and
building confidence among countries in the region."
</P>
<P>
They also endorsed the participation of Mongolia in the ARF,
which, initiated in 1993, is now participated by the ASEAN members
including Brunei, Indonesia, Laos, Malaysia, Myanmar, the
Philippines, Singapore, Thailand and Vietnam; its two observers
Cambodia and Papua New Guinea and dialogue partners -- Australia,
Canada, China, India, Japan, New Zealand, South Korea, Russia, the
European Union and the United States.
</P>
<P>
The AMM also discussed questions including the Middle East,
nuclear tests in South Asia and international economic issues.
</P>
</TEXT>
