<HEADLINE> ASEAN Deplores Nuclear Tests in South Asia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 25 (Xinhua) -- Member countries of the Southeast
Asian
Nations (ASEAN) Saturday criticized India and Pakistan for their
nuclear
tests conducted in May, saying the tests "raised the specter of a
nuclear
arms race."
</P>
<P>
"The foreign ministers deplored the series of nuclear tests
conducted
recently in South Asia that exacerbated tension in the region and
raised
the specter of a nuclear arms race," said a joint communique
issued here
Saturday afternoon at the end of the two-day 31st ASEAN
Ministerial
Meeting attended by the foreign ministers of the nine ASEAN
countries.
</P>
<P>
India carried out nuclear detonations in mid-May and Pakistan
responded with nuclear tests by the end of the same month.
</P>
<P>
The ASEAN foreign ministers called on all countries which have
not
done so to adhere to the Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty (NPT)
and
Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty "in recognition of the overwhelming
interest to establish a nuclear-free world."
</P>
<P>
They also called on the nuclear-weapon states to take concrete
and
timely measures toward the total elimination of nuclear weapons in

compliance with the provisions of the NPT. 
</P>
