<HEADLINE> Cambodian NEC Chairman Confident About Election </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, July 25 (Xinhua) -- Cambodia's National Election
Committee (NEC) chairman Chheng Phon on Saturday dismissed jitters
about the upcoming election, expressing belief the election would
produce a legitimate government.
</P>
<P>
"There should be no doubt that the election will pave the way
for the establishment of a government that will be able to lead
the Cambodian people toward peace and development," Chheng Phon
said in an interview with Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
An estimated 5.4 million Cambodians will go to the polls on
Sunday to elect a National Assembly, a major step toward the
setting up of a government.
</P>
<P>
Three major parties, the ruling Cambodian People's Party (CPP)
led by co-premier Hun Sen, the FUNCINPEC of deposed co-premier
Prince Norodom Ranariddh, and the Sam Rainsy Party named after the
former finance minister, are contending for seats of the National
Assembly.
</P>
<P>
The Cambodian people widely expect the election will end
decades of war that has wrecked havoc on the impoverished country.
</P>
<P>
Chheng Phon said the NEC, an independent organization
responsible for preparing the election, had been doing its best to
ensure the election be free, fair and credible.
</P>
<P>
There have been reports about irregularities, behind-the-scene
intimidation and incidents of violence prior to the election.
</P>
<P>
Sam Rainsy, also a prominent opposition leader, told a press
conference on Saturday that the 24,000 observers dispatched by his
party were subject to intimidation.
</P>
<P>
He said there had been "disguised crimes" intended to
intimidate supporters of his party and FUNCINPEC, a reference to
remarks by the CPP which refuted any linkage of previous crimes
with the election.
</P>
<P>
More than 100 election-related killings had reportedly taken
place.
</P>
<P>
Chheng Phon said the NEC has worked out 11-point regulations to
prevent intimidation and violence. These regulations, he said,
include the training of election workers and observers, and
punishment for those who violate the rules.
</P>
<P>
He said about 700 international and 33,000 local observers have
fanned out across the country to guarantee the transparency and
legitimacy of the elections.
</P>
<P>
He said the three-phase election had successfully completed the
first two stages -- voter registration and campaigning.
</P>
<P>
"I believe the last phase of casting and counting votes will
also be successful," Chheng Phon said.
</P>
<P>
"There should be no doubt that the election will show the will
and correct choice of the Cambodian people," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980725.0120 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ASEAN Asks Japan for Measures to Strengthen Financial System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 25 (Xinhua) -- The Association of Southeast Asian
Nations
(ASEAN) Saturday urged Japan to implement economic measures and
put its
own economy in order to help ASEAN countries get out of the
year-old
financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
In a joint communique issued at the end of the two-day 31st
ASEAN
Ministerial Meeting here Saturday afternoon, foreign ministers
from the
nine ASEAN members "called on Japan to expedite the implementation
of its
economic measures in support of the economic recovery of ASEAN
countries."
</P>
<P>
They also asked Japan to put its economy on the right track,
saying,
"Japan's determination to strengthen its financial system and to
put its
economy back on the path of self-sustained and domestic demand-led
growth
is important to the recovery of the Asian economies."
</P>
<P>
Japan is ASEAN's biggest creditor country. The recent turmoil
in the
Japanese financial system, including a fast-declining Japanese
yen, and
its economy as a whole has seriously affected the recovery of
ASEAN
economies, which have been plagued by problems such as currency
devaluation, bank liquidity problems, flight of capital, bank and
factory
closedowns, high inflation and unemployment.
</P>
<P>
The ministers also asked the G-7 industrialized countries --
Britain,
Canada, France, Germany, Italy, Japan and the United States -- "to
lead
international efforts and coordinate policy responses in resolving
the
financial crisis," which they said has become "a global concern."
</P>
<P>
On regional and international assistance programs, the ASEAN
ministers
said international and regional financial institutions as well as
friendly donor countries "need to consider the overall impact of
structural adjustment measures, which are being implemented by the

affected countries, on the underprivileged and vulnerable sectors
of
their societies."
</P>
<P>
Some affected ASEAN countries have obtained loans and
assistance from
the International Monetary Fund and other organizations, some of
which
imposed conditions including drastic structural adjustments such
as cuts
in welfare benefits for the poor people and privatization.
</P>
<P>
The ASEAN ministers in their communique also urged these donor
countries and financial institutions to implement the agreed
commitments
to enable the affected countries to continue their contributions
in
maintaining the stability of the region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
