<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ASEAN Signs 2nd Protocol to Treaty of Amity, Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 25 (Xinhua) -- The nine member countries of the
Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) and Cambodia signed
here Saturday the Second Protocol to the Treaty of Amity and
Cooperation in Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
The protocol amends Article 18 of the treaty to confer the
right of consent for accession by non-Southeast Asian states to
the treaty only to Southeast Asian nations.
</P>
<P>
The amendment allows non-Southeast Asian countries to accede to
the treaty which will provide them the legal framework for the
conduct of cooperative relations with states in Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
The treaty is a major landmark in the pursuit of ASEAN's
objective of making Southeast Asia a zone of peace, freedom and
neutrality.
</P>
<P>
The treaty was approved at the first ASEAN Summit held in Bali,
Indonesia, in February 1976, by the ASEAN countries.
</P>
<P>
The purpose of the treaty was to "promote perpetual peace,
everlasting amity and cooperation among their peoples which would
contribute to their strength, solidarity and closer relationship."
</P>
<P>
Papua New Guinea, through the first protocol approved in Manila
in December 1987, became the first and, thus far, the only
non-ASEAN state to accede to the treaty. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980725.0123 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ASEAN Reiterates Hope for Free, Fair Cambodian Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 25 (Xinhua) -- The Association of Southeast Asian
Nations (ASEAN) here Saturday reiterated its hope for "free, fair
and credible" elections in Cambodia.
</P>
<P>
The ASEAN foreign ministers said in a joint communique issued
after the 31st ASEAN Ministerial Meeting (AMM) that "free, fair
and credible" polls will facilitate the restoration of peace and
political stability in the country.
</P>
<P>
Cambodia will hold general elections on July 26 to elect a
prime minister. The country plunged into turmoil after First Prime
Minister Norodom Ranariddh was ousted last year.
</P>
<P>
The ASEAN foreign ministers noted the preparations made by the
Cambodian government and acknowledged the efforts of the ASEAN
Troika (Indonesia, Thailand the Philippines), the Friends of
Cambodia and the United Nations in support of this undertaking.
</P>
<P>
The Friends of Cambodia, a private group including Japan, the
United States, Russia, the European Union and some other donors,
has been working for the restoration of peace and stability in
Cambodia.
</P>
<P>
In the joint communique, the ministers also called for the
intensification of consultations with Cambodia to facilitate its
admission into ASEAN.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in their respective statements at the 31st AMM, they
voiced their support to have Cambodia as a new ASEAN member. Some
countries hope that Cambodia can join ASEAN at the end of this
year or next year.
</P>
<P>
However, Philippine Foreign Undersecretary Lauro Baja said
earlier at a press conference that Cambodia's admission to ASEAN
will depend on the outcome of the general elections.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN includes Brunei, Indonesia, Laos, Malaysia, Myanmar, the
Philippines, Singapore, Thailand and Vietnam. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
