<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ASEAN Enhances Cooperation to Address Financial Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 25 (Xinhua) -- The member countries of the
Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) decided here
Saturday to strengthen economic cooperation to address the ongoing
Asian financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN foreign ministers said in a joint communique issued after
the 31st ASEAN Ministerial Meeting (AMM) that they supports the
efforts by ASEAN finance ministers to strengthen the financial
systems of the member countries.
</P>
<P>
They strongly endorsed the finance ministers' decision to
establish an ASEAN surveillance mechanism to closely monitor
regional macroeconomic and financial indicators and to serve as an
early warning system.
</P>
<P>
The ministers also supported the finance ministers' decision to
encourage the use of regional currencies for promoting intra-ASEAN
trade and the use of bilateral payments arrangements on a
voluntary basis between individual ASEAN countries.
</P>
<P>
They underlined the importance of intra-ASEAN trade as an
engine of recovery of the ASEAN economies which have been gripped
and crippled by the Asian financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
In the communique, the ministers welcomed the Second ASEAN
Informal Summit's decision to accelerate the implementation of the
ASEAN Free Trade Area and the ASEAN Investment Area, saying the
decision reflects the member countries' strong commitment to
economic cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The Second ASEAN Informal Summit was held in Kuala Lumpur,
Malaysia, on December 14-16 last year.
</P>
<P>
The foreign ministers also said in the communique that they
were encouraged by the implementation of the Common Effective
Preferential Tariffs (CEPT) scheme, according to which ASEAN
member countries must cut tariffs to not more than 5 percent by
the year 2003.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the foreign ministers noted that Laos and Myanmar,
which joined ASEAN last year, have begun the implementation of the
CEPT scheme on January 1 this year.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN groups Brunei, Indonesia, Laos, Malaysia, Myanmar,
Singapore, the Philippines, Thailand and Vietnam. Cambodia and
Papua New Guinea attended the two-day 31st AMM as observers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
