<HEADLINE> Northern China Increasing Infrastructure Spending </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAIYUAN, July 25 (Xinhua) -- North China's Shanxi Province has
added 3.2 billion yuan (385 million US dollars) to its original
spending plan of 52.5 billion yuan for infrastructure construction
this year.
</P>
<P>
Provincial authorities say they hope that the total investment
alone will help increase economic growth 7 percent and help the
province reach its goal of 11 percent.
</P>
<P>
About 18.4 billion yuan will come from the Central Government
and the remaining 37.3 billion yuan from the local government and
other sources. Funds from non-government organizations are
expected to increase to 5 billion yuan, pushing total
infrastructure spending to 60 billion yuan in the province.
</P>
<P>
The increased spending will make infrastructure the province's
biggest area for new jobs, local planning officials say.
</P>
<P>
Highway construction funds will increase to 6.7 billion yuan
this year, creating 150,000 jobs.
</P>
<P>
As more infrastructure projects are completed, 830,000 kw of
power generating capacity will be added in 1998, and people in 10
prefectures and cities will have access to piped natural gas this
year, officials say. 
</P>
</TEXT>
