<DOCNO> XIE19980725.0133 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mandela Paid 60 Cows for Marriage to Machel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 25 (Xinhua) -- South African President
Nelson Mandela's clan held secret negotiations with the Machel
clan in Mozambique before Mandela's marriage to Graca Machel.
</P>
<P>
The parties agreed that Mandela would pay 60 prime cattle for
Graca's hand in marriage, Saturday Star newspaper reported.
</P>
<P>
The talks, which lasted two months, were full of symbolic and
traditional customs required during negotiations for such an
auspicious union, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
The extraordinary mission began in April when a "task force"
of royal members from Mandela's Tembu clan was sent to
Mozambique.
</P>
<P>
True to tradition, Mandela's uncles went to the future bride's
family to negotiate the number of cattle wanted for the bride.
</P>
<P>
The whole procedure took about two months and several trips.
</P>
<P>
It could have taken longer if negotiations were not so smooth,
for instance if the family had not wanted their child to marry
into that particular family. It went faster than usual because
all parties were enthusiastic about the match, said the paper,
quoting King Buyelekhaya Zwelibanzi and senior members of the
Tembu royal court.
</P>
<P>
The first step in the secretive negotiations was when Graca
officially informed her family about the impending visitors but
did not reveal who they were and where they were coming from.
</P>
<P>
The Machel family then set a date for the mysterious visitors'
arrival, April, in this case.
</P>
<P>
The initial contact, called ukucelwa, took place at night when
Mandela's clan delegates formally asked for Graca's hand in
marriage. The Tembu clan visitors were allowed into the house and
asked to identify themselves and justify why they wanted to
create kinship through Graca.
</P>
<P>
They were well taken care of and the visit did not last more
than five hours. But before they left, both parties agreed on the
next date to negotiate the number of cows to be paid for lobola,
or bridal price.
</P>
<P>
When the delegation came back, both parties told each other
what they expected from one another. According to custom,
Mandela and Graca were not involved in the second discussion, nor
was their input sought.
</P>
<P>
At some point during these negotiations, the parties agreed
that Mandela would pay 60 prime cattle for Graca's hand in
marriage.
</P>
<P>
Then, at the meeting, a date was set for the transfer of the
cows, and lastly the date for the wedding was set.
</P>
<P>
Asked whether he thought the lobola was justified, King
Zwelibanzi replied: "The number of cows involved in lobola is
nobody's business. Even if Rolihlahla (Mandela) had paid a
million cows for Graca, she is worth every bristle of hair and
hoof !"
</P>
<P>
When asked if Winnie Madikizela-Mandela had strategically
attended a funeral in the Eastern Cape at the time of the
wedding, the king replied: "This is another typical rumor, that
we have fallen out with her. She is a child of this family, we
never divorced her as a clan. Only tow people divorced. We still
love her."
</P>
<P>
Themba Sangoni, the presidential aide in the Eastern Cape,
would not confirm how the cows were exchanged. He also refused
to disclose how often the emissaries traveled to Maputo to close
the lobola deal with the Machels.
</P>
<P>
"The president is not a boy, and it is a matter between him
and those he chooses to tell," he said.
</P>
<P>
King Zwelibanzi this week also scotched rumors that a rift had
developed between Mandela and his clan members over the marriage.
He described the controversy as a fabrication by a loose-footed,
bitter pretender to the throne."
</P>
<P>
Last Monday, Chief Ndaba Zwelodumo Mtirara claimed the Tembu
clan was up in arms over Mandela's planned wedding to Graca.
</P>
<P>
In a radio interview, he said Mandela had acted in a
disrespectful manner, unbecoming an honored member of the royal
family. He went on further to say Mandela would face serious
consequences, which would be decided upon by the royal house,
King Zwelibanzi and senior members of the royal court.
</P>
<P>
Zwelibanzi distanced himself and the royal house from the
"heretical utterances of Chief Ndaba Zwelodumo."
</P>
<P>
The king said: "There is nothing wrong for Rolihlahla to
publicly court a woman he loves and have a relationship with her
outside of marriage, considering his age, royal status and
circumstance.
</P>
<P>
"His marrying her is actually a great sign of respect and
confirms his greatness -- he has given the relationship dignity."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
