<HEADLINE> Talks With Israelis Not on Troop Withdrawal: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 25 (Xinhua) -- A senior advisor to Palestinian
leader Yasser Arafat has said the continued Israeli-Palestinian
talks this week will not discuss the Israeli withdrawal from the
West Bank, Egypt's Voice of Arabs radio reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Ahmed Tibi, Arafat's advisor on Israeli affairs, said that
during their meetings next week, Arafat's deputy Mahmoud Abbas and
Israeli Public Security Minister Avigdor Kahalani would not touch
on the overdue troop pullout.
</P>
<P>
They would discuss the problems facing the Palestinians in
Jerusalem, Tibi said, without elaborating on what are the problems.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the Palestinians would not resume talks with
the Israelis on the troop withdrawal until Israel accepts the
proposal made by the United States.
</P>
<P>
Abbas and Israeli Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai held talks
last Sunday, but ended in failure. This was the first high-level
talks between the two sides in months.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. has reportedly called on Israel to withdraw from
another 13.1 percent of the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians have accepted the proposal, but Israel has
rejected it citing that the proposed withdrawal endangers its
security interests.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian National Authority has full or partial control
over 27 percent of the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Tibi urged the U.S. administration to go public with its
initiative in an effort to revive the stalled peace process.
</P>
<P>
"If the U.S. does not take such a step, Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu will go on with slowly killing the peace
march," he added. 
</P>
