<HEADLINE> Zambian Government Urged to Curb Brutal Killings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, July 25 (Xinhua) -- Zambia's businessmen and workers
have urged the government to quickly move in and curb the recent
upsurge of brutal killings and warned that foreign investors will
start fleeing the country if nothing is done.
</P>
<P>
The Zambia Federation of Employers (ZFE) and the Zambia
Congress of Trade Unions (ZCTU) issued the warning in Lusaka
Friday during a consultative labor council, Times of Zambia
reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
In the past few months, said ZFE President Francis Simenda,
foreign investors have been attacked and killed in brutal
circumstances, and if the situation continues, investors will flee
Zambia.
</P>
<P>
He urged the government to find resources to beef up the
police to make them more effective.
</P>
<P>
"We can't afford to continue losing lives. If it means
diverting resources to the police to curb the situation, let us
do so," Simenda said.
</P>
<P>
ZCTU President Fackson Shamenda attributed the rising crime
wave to the de-motivated police service and demanded that the
government improve their salaries and conditions of service.
</P>
<P>
Labor Minister Newstead Zimba said the government is equally
concerned with the development and is appealing to people with
information that could help to curb crimes to report to the
police.
</P>
<P>
"It is true that security in the country is now worrying. I am
grateful that both ZCTU and ZFE have expressed concern over the
matter," he said.
</P>
<P>
Recently, gunmen have shot dead a number of businessmen with
the latest being a managing director Vincent Chalwe of a bureau
de change who was killed last Tuesday morning in a dramatic
robbery. 
</P>
</TEXT>
