<HEADLINE> Chinese Island Province Develops Its Marine Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAIKOU, July 25 (Xinhua) -- Policy-makers on China's southern
island province of Hainan are looking at the maritime industry as
a source of help for stagnant economy.
</P>
<P>
Average growth in the maritime industry for the past decade was
3 times GDP growth, and in 1997, the sector had 11.6 billion yuan
(1.397 billion US dollars) in output, a quarter of the provincial
GDP.
</P>
<P>
Du Qinglin, Hainan's Party Secretary, says the local authorities
will make the most of the rapid, efficient, and forceful growth in
the maritime industry to help economic growth and build Hainan
into a powerful marine economy.
</P>
<P>
Hainan is China's smallest province, with 34,000 square
kilometers of land, but it has more than 2 million sq km of ocean,
with over 10,000 species of marine life, including some 1,000
types of fishes and 200 kinds of algae.
</P>
<P>
It has 1,800 kilometers of coastline, with 18 ports and another
60 potential port locations. It also has 200,000 ha of shallows
that could be used for aquaculture.
</P>
<P>
The province plans to develop its petroleum resources and
refining and related industries. South China Sea reserves are
estimated at 70 billion tons of petroleum and gas.
</P>
<P>
Hainan wants to bring its marine industrial output up to 15
billion yuan in the next 2 years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
