<HEADLINE> Uganda Deputy Speaker Forced to Resign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, July 25 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan Deputy Speaker of
Parliament, Betty Okwir, has finally bowed to mounting pressure
from the top leadership of National Resistance Movement and
resigned her job only three days before the speaker is to
be elected.
</P>
<P>
A senior official in the office of the clerk to parliament
confirmed the resignation over the weekend, the Monitor daily
reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The report said the deputy speaker was offered a ministerial
post in the cabinet.
</P>
<P>
Previously, she vowed to remain on the post in spite of
pressure piled on her to quit.
</P>
<P>
"No. I am not resigning and nobody has talked to me about
resigning. Why? Why should I resign?" she was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
There were allegations that former speaker James Wapakhabulo,
who was elected the Movement's National Political Commissar last
week, was chosen to persuade Okwir to quit.
</P>
<P>
If she refused to do so, they could turn the screws on and
possibly force her out via a vote of no confidence, said the report.
</P>
<P>
Okwir's resignation was taken as preparing ground for Edward
Sekandi's entrance into the race as deputy speaker creating
favorable conditions for Minister Francis Ayume's candidature for
the Speakership.
</P>
<P>
Sekandi is widely considered a big rival for Ayume who was
chosen by the Movement leadership caucus as candidate for the top
post in the House.
</P>
<P>
"If Okwir stays in office it wil be difficult for Ayume to
take over as Speaker, we can't have two northerners steering
Parliament," one member of parliament said.
</P>
<P>
The report said President Yoweri Museveni and his confidants
are also wary that the rebellious mood sweeping the House over
the executive's push for Ayume, could make it easy for someone to
come from the floor and defeat him if Okwir is still deputy
speaker. 
</P>
</TEXT>
