<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladeshi PM Calls for All Possible Steps to Combat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, July 25 (Xinhua) -- Bangladeshi Prime Minister Sheikh
Hasina has directed government officials to take all necessary
measures to face the flood and post-flood situation in the
country.
</P>
<P>
"You'll have to take all possible steps to save the people from
flood and remain alert so that none dies in post-flood diseases,"
Hasina told officials at a meeting of the National Disaster
Management Council on Friday, media reports here said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
She urged all political parties and non-governmental
organizations in the country to take part in the rescue, relief
and rehabilitation work for the flood victims, as it was not
possible for the government alone to ensure all possible
assistance to rehabilitate the huge number of flood victims.
</P>
<P>
Thirty-five of the country's 64 districts were attacked by
flooding affecting nearly 10 million people, officials at the
meeting said.
</P>
<P>
Press reports, however, put the number of flood victims at over
10 million in 54 districts, where 61 people had died from flood,
standing crops on 381,000 acres of land had been ravaged, 29,000
homes wrecked and 194,000 houses partially damaged by monsoon
floods since the monsoon season began in the country in early
July.
</P>
<P>
As diseases usually claim more lives in the post-flood
situation, steps should be taken to ensure adequate medicines,
water purification tablets, and other essentials for the
flood-affected people, according to the prime minister, who also
directed the officials to maintain adequate food stock and ensure
supply of seedlings for farmers.
</P>
<P>
About 7,000 people were attacked by diarrhea, with only four
deaths reported, due to precautionary measures, according to the
officials. Some 2,000 medical teams had been formed and were being
sent to the flood-affected areas, they said.
</P>
<P>
Officials said that there was an adequate stock of food grains
to face any possible disaster and steps were being taken to make
more stocks as further precautionary measures. The government
machinery in the flood- affected areas were working "vigorously"
to ensure food and shelter to the flood victims, and sufficient
relief and medicine were being supplied in the affected areas,
they said.
</P>
<P>
The government had reportedly sanctioned more than 4 million
(about 85,000 U.S. dollars) and 2,481 tons of rice or wheat
together with other relief materials for the flood-stricken
population.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the recurrent floods in the country, the prime
minister laid emphasis on timely dredging of rivers. The river
embankments could be constructed by the dredged soil, which would
help protect land and increase the depth of the rivers, she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
