<HEADLINE> 3 Lebanese Civilians Killed in South Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, July 25 (Xinhua) -- Three Lebanese civilians were
killed Friday night by a roadside bomb in south Lebanon, the
Orient radio reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The blast took place at the al Muna village in the country's
southern city of Nabatieh.
</P>
<P>
No one has claimed responsibility for the attack, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
But the radio quoted Lebanese security sources as saying
that when the bomb blew up, an Israeli pilotless warplane
was buzzing overhead.
</P>
<P>
Israel has created the 1,200-square-kilometer "South Lebanon
Security Zone" since 1985 with the claimed aim of protecting its
north from cross-border attacks by Lebanese guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian-backed Hezbollah, or Party of God, has been
fighting a guerrilla war to oust the 2,000-strong Israeli
occupation forces from south Lebanon. 
</P>
