<BODY>
<HEADLINE> National Language Policy Called for in Zimbabwe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 25 (Xinhua) --A senior Zimbabwean official has
called for the launching of a comprehensive national language
policy to maintain the country's mother language, culture and
values.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe's present and future generations are in danger of
losing their mother language, culture and values unless a
comprehensive national language policy is adopted, said Minister
of Education, Sport and Culture, Gabriel Machinga.
</P>
<P>
The minister made the remarks Friday after he was presented
with the report on the formulation of a national language policy
by the national language policy advisory panel, the Daily Herald
reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
He said the country's vernacular languages were at the risk of
dying out as the post-independence generation prefers to speak
English with the blessings of their parents.
</P>
<P>
As a result, primary school pupils have been progressively
performing badly in the main Shona and Ndebele vernacular
languages.
</P>
<P>
"We cannot dissociate ourselves from our mother tongue. Those
children denied a chance to learn vernacular languages will lose
their culture," the minister said.
</P>
<P>
Machinga said while the world was becoming a global village,
there was need to distinguish our languages by uplifting them. By
the same token "we should not be globalized so much so that we
lose our national languages."
</P>
<P>
The national language advisory panel has recommended that two
different bodies be formed to implement, monitor and review the
national language policy provisions.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980725.0152 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey Renews Security Guarantee for Turkish Cypriots </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, July 25 (Xinhua) -- Turkish President Suleyman Demirel
vowed Saturday Turkey will take necessary measures to protect the
security of Turkish Cypriots living in northern Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
The president made the statement at Ankara's Esenboga Airport
before his departure for an one-day visit to northern Cyprus at the
invitation of Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash.
</P>
<P>
This was Demirel's first visit to northern Cyprus since he
became president in 1993.
</P>
<P>
Demirel criticized the "wrong messages" sent to Greek Cypriots
by the European Union (EU), warning it could lead to "the
destruction of the framework of the settlement and parameter in
the process of the United Nations conference."
</P>
<P>
Both Turkey and Turkish Cypriots were angered by the EU's
decision to start membership negotiations with the Greek
Cypriot-led Cypriot government in April.
</P>
<P>
Denktash has repeated that the Cypriot government has no right
to represent the Turkish Cypriots. He quited the peace talks with
the Greek Cypriots in August last year to protest against the EU's
decision.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into the Greek Cypriot-dominated south
and the Turkish Cypriot-controlled north since 1974 when Turkish
troops took over northern Cyprus in response to an abortive
pro-Athens coup in Nicosia.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Cypriots unilaterally declared in 1983 the "Turkish
Republic of Northern Cyprus" in the north, which was recognized
only by Turkey, the staunch allay of Turkish Cypriots.
</P>
<P>
Tensions have been running high since early last year when
Cyprus ordered a Russian anti-aircraft missile system in a bid to
boost its air defense. Turkey has threatened to strike the
missiles if they are deployed as scheduled late this year.
</P>
<P>
Demirel said that he believed "that two Turkish States in the
Mediterranean Sea will intensify strong solidarity and
cooperation during the 21st century."
</P>
<P>
Besides the security guarantees, Turkey also attaches great
importance to the development of the economy of northern Cyprus,
added Demirel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
