<DOCNO> XIE19980725.0155 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Study: Postsurgical Radiation May Reduce Survival Rates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, July 25 (Xinhua) -- A study released Saturday said
that postoperative radiotherapy appears to reduce survival rates
among patients with non-small-cell lung cancer.
</P>
<P>
The study, published in the July 25th issue of The Lancet and
conducted by a group of researchers led by Dr Lesley A Stewart,
said that the research team analyzed updated data from nine
studies that assessed the effects of the therapy among more than
2,100 patients with non-small-cell lung cancer.
</P>
<P>
Of 1,072 patients who had surgery alone, 411 were still living,
the team found. By comparison, only 349 of 1,056 patients who had
postoperative radiation were still alive. Patients who had
postsurgical radiation ran a 21 percent higher risk of dying than
those who had surgery alone, the study added.
</P>
<P>
"The results therefore indicate that postoperative radiotherapy
should not be routinely used to treat these patients," writes
Stewart, the author of the study.
</P>
<P>
The researchers noted that information on causes of death among
the patients in the nine studies was limited. But they suggested
the toxic effects as one of main causes of the additional deaths.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
