<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sino-French Joint Venture Producing New Mini Bus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, July 25 (Xinhua) -- A production line of "Trafic" mini
bus began operation recently by Sino-French Sanjiang Renault
Automobile Co.
</P>
<P>
The new assembling line, which is the first phase of the
venture based in Xiaogan City of Hubei Province, is designed to
produce 10,000 "Trafic" buses of seven, eight and twelve-seat
series annually.
</P>
<P>
The second phase, which will be ready in 2000, will bring the
annual capacity to 50,000 Trafic vehicles.
</P>
<P>
Total investment of the project amounts to 98 million US
dollars, which is shared by the Chinese investor--China Sanjiang
Space Group and the French partner--Renault Automobile on a
55-to-45-percent ratio.
</P>
<P>
The project will proceed strictly according to the product,
mangement and sale service standards of Renault, which requires
the establishment of the service networks prior to the start of
the car sale, and the service networks exclusively monopolying the
sale right of parts and components.
</P>
<P>
The joint venture, which went into small-scale production in
1994, has already set up a sound sales service network in 60 large
and medium-sized cities in 30 provinces, municipalities and
autonomous regions in China. It has turned out and sold over 3,000
Trafic business vehicles, station wagons, cash-transfers, and
ambulances, with average sale amounting to 250,000 yuan (30,120 US
dollars) per vehicle. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980725.0160 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kabayeva Sweeps 3 Golds in Rhythmic Gymnastics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, July 24 (Xinhua) -- Alina Kabayeva of Russia swept
three out of four gold medals in the rhythmic gymnastics
competition, while the United States beat Australia 93-85 overtime
in the men's basketball final here on Friday at the Goodwill Games.
</P>
<P>
Kabayeva, who took the all-around title yesterday, conquered
the referees with tremendous talent in the individual events,
finishing first in the ribbon, the clubs and hoop. Olympic bronze
medalist Yelena Vitrichenko of Ukriane prevented her from a clean
sweep of the golds by winning the rope with a slight margin over
the delicate Russian.
</P>
<P>
The day's another gold medal was won by China's Yu Zhuocheng in
the men's one-meter springboard.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. basketball team, including no NBA professionals, was e
xtended fully into overtime after the regulation ended 79-all. The
American college players fended off the never-say-die Aussies to
win the tough showdown.
</P>
<P>
Shane Heal was the biggest gun for Australia, scoring game-high
38 points. Andrew Gaze added 25 and Chris Anstey had nine. The
rest of the line-up only contributed a total of 13 points.
</P>
<P>
Andre Miller scored 15 of his 18 points in the second half for
the U.S. team, while Elton Brand and Wally Szczerbiak each hit 15
points.
</P>
<P>
The score was seasawed all the way till the last two minutes.
The first half ended 40-40, and Miller forced the game into the
overtime with a steal-and-driving layup with 55 seconds remaining.
</P>
<P>
The Americans used their speed and better board control to ruin
the Aussies, who lost their rhythm and composure in the overtime.
</P>
<P>
Trailing 85-89 with one minute to go, the Americans scored four
straight points to seal the victory.
</P>
<P>
In the game to determine the third place, Lithuania, bronze
medalists in the 1992 and 1996 Olympics, beat defending champions
Puerto Rico 119-75.
</P>
<P>
China's Yu Zhuocheng and Zhou Yilin met no challenge throughout
to sweep the top two medals of the men's one-meter springboard
diving this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Yu, world 3-meter springboard champion this year, overtook Zhou
in his final dive, winning the gold with a total of 426.24 points.
Zhuo, world silver medalist for the event this year, led the first
five round after registering a day's highest score 81.60 on his
second outing. He faded to second position, but still had 26
points to spare than the third placed Mark Ruiz of the United
States, who collected 395.52.
</P>
<P>
The competition was a Chinese affair from the first round,
which saw Zhou ranked first with 63.96 ahead of Yu's 63.18. Ruiz
was listed third trailig about 1.5 points.
</P>
<P>
Zhou, 24, widened the leading margin after second action, but
Yu narrowed the gap a bit in the third. After the fourth round,
Zhou placed first with 277.86, followed closely by Yu, 277.38.
Ruiz dropped a distance third with 256.02.
</P>
<P>
With the two Chinese fighting for the gold, Ruiz had to hold
off a strong surge from Andreas Wels of Germany in the bronze
battle. The German performed excellently in his final two dives,
gaining 72.00 and 73.47, but his efforts came still short, losing
only 2.18 points.
</P>
<P>
"I knew I could win through if I dive good in my last round.
That was the most difficult action and could bring me high point,"
said Yu, who gained his fame in 1993 when he won World Cup 3-meter
springboard title.
</P>
<P>
"I will do my best here to win the 3-meter title," added Yu,
who was selected as the Best Diver of the Year in 1994 by the U.S.
Swimming magzine.
</P>
<P>
Li Dazheng, leader of the Chinese diving team, told Xinhua that
the Chinese divers have strength to take five or six gold medals
here. "But we will meet strong challenge in the men's 3-meter
springboard and the platform."
</P>
<P>
In the men's beach volleyball competition, Brazil's tandem Para
Ferreira and Guilherme Marques overspiked Canada's John Child and
Mark Heese 15-11, and the U.S. team Adam Johnson and Karch Kiraly
nipped Ricci Luyties and Sinjin Smith, also Americans, 16-14 in
group A.
</P>
<P>
Paul Laciga and Martin Laciga, brothers from Switzerland, edged
defending champions Jan Kvahleim and Bjorn Maaseide of Norway
16-14, while Australia's pair Lee Zahner and Julien Prosser
overpowered Esteban Martinez and Martin Conde of Argentina 15-7.
</P>
</TEXT>
