<HEADLINE> Floods Hit Three Provinces in Central, East China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 25 (Xinhua) -- Floods in Hunan, Jiangxi and Hubei
provinces have killed 145 people and forced the emergency
relocation of 900,000 residents since last Friday, according to a
report issued yesterday by the Ministry of Civil Affairs.
</P>
<P>
Reports issued by the Ministry also indicate there have been
1,145 deaths caused by flooding since the beginning of this year,
"China Daily" said today.
</P>
<P>
The majority of deaths resulted from drownings, houses
collapsing, lightning, mud flows and landslides caused by mountain
torrents.
</P>
<P>
Floods in the three provinces have destroyed 250,000 houses and
damaged another 780,000, affecting 1.1 million residents in 71
counties.
</P>
<P>
The floods also affected one million hectares of cultivated
land, leaving 180,000 hectares of crops fruitless. Direct losses
are estimated to be at least 9.2 billion yuan(1.1 billion US
dollars).
</P>
<P>
As of July 15, flooding that started in June had affected more
than 140 million people, had destroyed 2.9 million houses and had
ruined 9 million hectares of crops.
</P>
<P>
To date, direct economic losses resulting from floods were
estimated at more than 94.8 billion yuan(11.4 billion US dollars),
the paper said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
