<DOCNO> XIE19980725.0163 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> American Investors Choose Internet Portals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, July 24 (Xinhua) -- Of the 58 million American
Internet users, 35 million are conducting some form of financial
services over the Web, according to a study by market research
firm Cyber Dialogue.
</P>
<P>
The study, released Thursday, shows that instead of banks or
brokerage houses, Internet portals such as American Online, Yahoo
and Quicken have become the key to financial services. American
consumers are primarily using these portals to access financial
services on the Internet, placing portal brand recognition above
traditional financial brand names online.
</P>
<P>
Out of the 18.1 million American users who manage their
investments online, more than 2 million "digital investors"
reported that the most frequently used site for managing their
finances is American Online's Personal Finance area, which is
accessed five times more often than the nearest established
brokerage branded Web site.
</P>
<P>
In fact, according to the study, financial services providers
cannot go online and rest on the laurels, depending on their
offline brand to bring in the hits. They must have a range of
online and offline service options available to obtain and retain
customers. More than 50 percent of American "digital investors"
use multiple sources to retrieve stock quotes, and nearly 20
percent use multiple brokerage sources when they trade.
</P>
<P>
"These findings tend to support the long-term valuations of
leading Internet portals," said Cyber Dialogue.
</P>
<P>
The survey also found that while only 3 million Internet users
perform a majority for their stock trades via the Internet, 18.1
million users are regularly engaged in some form of investment
activity via the Net, a 132 percent increase from 7.8 million
measured in the second quarter of 1997.
</P>
<P>
The study is based on interviews with 1,000 Internet users and
500 non-users. Respondents were asked about their use of online
and offline financial services usage. The survey was fielded in
the second quarter of 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
