<HEADLINE> Desalination Of Sea Water In Northern China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, July 25 (Xinhua) -- Tianjin, a port city about 100 km
east of Beijing, plans to use 70 million cubic meters of
desalted sea water by the year 2010, or 4 percent of its water
for industry and daily use, according to a Municipal Oceanic
Administration official.
</P>
<P>
With per capita fresh water resources only about a fourth the
world average, China has more than 300 cities with water shortage
problems, 14 of them coastal cities.
</P>
<P>
Tianjin has developed new desalination technology using
membrane and precipitating methods. The Dagang Power Plant can
annually produce 2.19 million tons of fresh water through
desalination.
</P>
<P>
Dagang can use 1.7 billion cubic meters of sea water for
cooling each year, and a third-phase sea water utilization project
is being prepared.
</P>
<P>
The municipal government plans to use sea water mainly as
industrial cooling water in coastal areas before the year 2010,
and after that it will be able to use it directly in industry and
for daily use. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
