<HEADLINE> Obuchi Urged To Get Japan's Economy Growing Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, July 25 (Xinhua) -- Local newspaper "The Dominion"
said in a Saturday's report that "More uncertainty was cast over
New Zealand's economic recovery last night when Japan's ruling
party elected Foreign Minister Keizo Obuchi its new leader and
almost certainly the next prime minister."
</P>
<P>
The paper noted that Mr. Obuchi faces the urgent task of
"lifting Japan's ailing economy out of its worst recession since
World War II".
</P>
<P>
It said that the health of the Japanese economy is "crucial to
the recovery of Asian countries and New Zealand."
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted New Zealand Foreign Minister Don McKinnon as
saying that he hoped Mr. Obuchi and his Liberal Democratic Party
"grasp the nettle".
</P>
<P>
"Japan is the big locomotive of the region, and we'd like to
see it moving out of the station. Once it starts moving it pulls
all the Asian carriages including ourselves and Australia behind
it," he said.
</P>
<P>
Speaking of New Zealand's worsening economic situation, the
paper quoted a New Zealand economist as saying "This is the
cumulative impact of Asia now hitting us."
</P>
<P>
The paper said that markets must now wait to see if Mr. Obuchi
can push through the policies necessary to fix Japan's crippled
banking sector and get its economy growing again.
</P>
<P>
"Though he has pledged economic reform, there is doubt over his
ability to make haste. Success will demand deft political footwork
and a delicate economic balancing act," it said.
</P>
<P>
According to the paper, a spokeswoman for New Zealand Prime
Minister Jenny Shipley said that New Zealand would extend its
congratulations to Mr. Obuchi on his appointment. Mr. Obuchi
"assumes the role at a very challenging time for his country and
we wish him well," she said.  
</P>
