<DOCNO> XIE19980725.0174 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka's Minister On SAPTA, SAFTA </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, July 25 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lankan Minister of Internal
and International Commerce T. Wickramaratne has said the South
Asian Preferential Trade Agreement (SAPTA) has given the correct
impetus to the South Asian Association for Regional Cooperation
(SAARC).
</P>
<P>
In a special interview with the official newspaper Daily News
here Friday, He also said the South Asian Free Trade Area (SAFTA)
was not a non-tariff barrier to globalization, but is a building
block and a stepping stone to globalization.
</P>
<P>
The leaders of the SAARC decided at the Male Summit in May last
year that the time from SAPTA to SAFTA be advanced from 2005 to
2001. that itself shows the positive attitude of the SAARC leaders
towards the globalization process, the Minister said.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that it is important that South Asia becomes a
single market so that it could marshal all the resources within
the region be it the material resources or human resources.
</P>
<P>
This could set the stage for joint ventures, alliances and
networks in order to be competitive in the global market, he
added.
</P>
<P>
The SAARC, formed in December 1985 to promote regional
cooperation in economic, social, cultural and other fields,
embraces Bangladesh, Bhutan, India, the Maldives, Nepal, Pakistan
and Sri Lanka.
</P>
<P>
On trade under SAFTA, which has been very small up to now, he
answered that once SAFTA comes into place, market distortions
would be eliminated.
</P>
<P>
He said as for the last two years, Sri Lanka's exports to SAPTA
 accounted for 15.8 million U.S. dollars while the imports from
SAFTA to Sri Lanka was only 12.5 million U.S. dollars. The trade
balance was in the country's favor by 3.3 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Answering the question on the differences of opinions about
SAFTA, the Minister noted that the real reason is that India has
vast market access and is afraid of competition. In Sri Lanka, he
said, the import tariffs are low. The maximum tariff is 35
percent. The tariff rate for gold, silver and textiles is zero.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980725.0175 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Obuchi Gets Tough Job as LDP President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, July 25 (Xinhua) -- Japanese Foreign Minister Keizo
Obuchi could hardly get relaxed after winning the presidential
race within the ruling Liberal Democratic Party (LDP) as several
thorny problems are awaiting him and his government to be formed.
</P>
<P>
As the newly-elected LDP chief, Obuchi, 61, is expected to be
prime minister to succeed Ryutaro Hashimoto later this month.
</P>
<P>
Obuchi was elected LDP chief at a time when Japan's economy is
going through the worst slump since the end of World War II. The
top task Obuchi has to face up is how to revitalize the ailing
economy.
</P>
<P>
In the fiscal year of 1997, Japan's gross domestic product grew
only 0.7 percent. Meanwhile, the jobless rate exceeded 4 percent,
the most unfavorable percentage since comparable figures were
first recorded in 1953.
</P>
<P>
Because of the stagnant economy, the LDP suffered a major
setback in the July 12 House of Councillors election, forcing
Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto to step down.
</P>
<P>
"The pressing issue facing us is to reconstruct the Japanese
economy and get rid of the people's uncertainty," Obuchi said at a
press conference shortly after winning the election.
</P>
<P>
"The Japanese economy bears responsibility for Asia and the
whole world. We hope to convert the minus growth into plus
growth," he said.
</P>
<P>
However, acknowledgement and hope are far away from being
sufficient to revive the sluggish economy. Turning the minus
growth into plus growth needs concrete and effective measures.
</P>
<P>
The first step Obuchi has to take is to give a clear impression
of his bold economic policies, political will and his ability to
carry them out so as to recover the confidence of people at home
and abroad, analysts pointed out.
</P>
<P>
To show the public and the rest of the world how determined he
is to tackle the country's economic woes, Obuchi should form a
truly capable cabinet that can overcome the economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
The immediate task for Obuchi is to rebuild the country's
battered financial sector as time is running out to dispose of
huge amounts of bad loans held by banks and other financial
institutions, which many believe are the root cause of the
country's economic predicament.
</P>
<P>
Besides this, policies, such as the large-scale permanent tax
cuts and the injection of public money, as Obuchi has already
pledged, must be implemented to stimulate the economy and improve
economic performance, they added.
</P>
<P>
Obuchi promised to carry out permanent tax cuts of 6 trillion
yen (about 42.9 billion U.S. dollars) before the election.
</P>
<P>
Another major task for Obuchi is how to unite his party and
coordinate relations with opposition parties.
</P>
<P>
Obuchi currently inherited a party that lacks not only majority
in the House of Councillors but also internal unity due to cracks
appeared during the heated and closely watched run-up to the
presidential election.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that some young LDP politicians claimed before
the election that they would leave the party if Obuchi won. If
this came true, a political vacuum would be created and a
political mess would be unavoidable.
</P>
<P>
Even if Obuchi, known as being very adept at political
adjustment and building a consensus, could have no problem in
uniting his own party, it seems that he would meet more
difficulties in coordinating relations with the opposition parties.
</P>
<P>
In response to his election as LDP president, opposition
parties demanded Friday the House of Representatives (the lower
house of parliament) be dissolved for a general election, citing
that the LDP would not take a stance aimed at making reforms.
</P>
<P>
As the LDP failed to hold a majority in the House of
Councillors, Obuchi has to solicit cooperation from opposition
parties so as to enact government-proposed bills.
</P>
<P>
Obuchi expressed the hope shortly after being elected that the
Diet (parliament) would pass legislation as soon as possible to
implement the "bridge bank" plan to clean up bad debts of the
country's failed financial institutions.
</P>
<P>
The LDP chief, hence the prime minister, is not an easy job for
Obuchi. Whether he could serve out smoothly the rest of
Hashimoto's term until the end of September, 1999, depends upon
how quickly he can promote measures to revive Japan's economy.
</P>
<P>
If the new government cannot produce tangible and positive
results soon in its management of the economy, the LDP is certain
to lose the next unified local elections scheduled for next
spring. That also means that the Obuchi government may crumble
before the next general election, some analysts noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
