<DOCNO> XIE19980725.0176 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NZ Yearly Trade deficit Exceeds One Bln NZ Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, July 25 (Xinhua) -- New Zealand's foreign trade
balance was a deficit of 1,009 million NZ dollars (524.7 million
U.S. dollars) for the year ended June 1998, Deputy Government
Statistician Ian Ewing announced in a media release, which was
circulated here Saturday.
</P>
<P>
He added the deficit for the previous 12 months was 290 NZ
dollars (150.8 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Figures showed that Imports to New Zealand in June exceeded
exports, resulting in a trade deficit of 15 million NZ dollars
(7.8 million U.S. dollars). This compares with a trade surplus of
150 million NZ dollars (78 million U.S. dollars) for the month of
June 1997.
</P>
<P>
Ewing said that for June 1998, New Zealand's imports were 1,836
million NZ dollars (954.7 million U.S. dollars) and its exports
were 1,821 million NZ dollars (946.9 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
"The trend in the monthly merchandise trade balance has been
negative for seven months and is worsening," he said.
</P>
<P>
"The imports trend is rising and increasingly exceeds the
exports trend which is falling," Ewing said, adding: "Exports to
Asia are still declining."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
