<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bulgarian Population Expected to Drop in Coming Decades </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, July 24 (Xinhua) -- The population in Bulgaria is likely
to drop from around 8.3 million to 7 million in the coming
decades, according to a study organized by the United Nations
Economic Commission for Europe.
</P>
<P>
Dimiter Filipov from the Bulgarian Academy of Sciences
presented the findings to a news conference Friday.
</P>
<P>
The study, covering 2,725 women aged 18 to 45, used a standard
questionnaire applied in other 24 countries.
</P>
<P>
It found that marriage and child bearing come at an earlier age
in Bulgaria than in other European countries.
</P>
<P>
The first marriage age for women in this nation is 18 to 22 as
against 30 in Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
The average number of children per family is 2.1, which means a
zero population growth for Bulgaria.
</P>
<P>
The birth rate among Bulgarian Turks and Gypsies is expected to
drop even more dramatically as these ethnic groups are entering a
period of transition characterized by fewer births, he said.
</P>
<P>
Most of the Bulgarian women who do not want children say the
rising cost of raising children, especially when they grow up, is
the main reason. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980725.0179 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Panamanian Banana Export Drops in First Six Months 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANAMA CITY, July 24 (Xinhua) -- Panama's banana exports
dropped 33 percent in the first half of this year, compared to the
same period of 1997, the Commerce and Industry Ministry said on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
Panamanian banana export in the period slid to 12 million
boxes, each weighing 18.14 kilograms, from 16.8 million in the
same period of the last year.
</P>
<P>
The shocking 57-day strike by workers in the Chiriqui Land
Company of the Pacific division and the "El Nino" weather
phenomenon are to blame for the situation.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that only 24 million boxes will be exported in
1998, as against 33.3 million in 1997, the ministry added.
</P>
<P>
Banana is one of Panama's major agriculture items for export,
garnering more than 120 million U.S. dollars per year. More than
10,000 Panamanians are working in this industry with its products
mainly supplied to the United States, Germany, and Spain. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
