<HEADLINE> Swiss Beach Tandem Spikes Defending Champions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, July 24 (Xinhua) -- The Laciga brothers of
Switzerland eliminated the Norweigian tandem of Jan Kvalheim and
Bjorn Maaseide from medal contention here Friday evening as the
Goodwill Games started its final session of round-robin men's
beach volleyball competition.
</P>
<P>
Martin and Paul Laciga rallied from a 14-11 deficit to score a
16-14 decision over Kvalheim and Maaseide to oust the defending
champions. The Norweigians had to win the match against the Swiss
along with posting a 15-11 or better winning score to advance.
</P>
<P>
However, the Lacigas mounted a tremendous comeback to tie the
Norway's pair in the group B standings with 1-2 marks. The
Norweigians had a better point differential to earn a spot in the
fifth-sixth playoff while the Lacigas will play for seventh in the
overall standings.
</P>
<P>
With the Swiss win, Martin Conde and Esteban Martinez of
Argentia will advance to the medal round as the second-place group
B team with Julien Prosser and Leo Zahner of Australia winning the
pool. Both teams tied with a 2-1 mark with the Aussies have a
point differential edge.
</P>
<P>
Prosser and Zahner beat Conda and Martinez 15-7 today.
</P>
<P>
The Brazilian tandem of Guilherme Marques and Para Ferreira
finished their round-robin group A play with a 15-11 win over John
Child and Mark Heese of Canada.
</P>
<P>
The Brazilian pair, the top-rated team on the 1998 FIVA beach
volleyball world tour, were down 6-0 to the Canadians before
rallying to take a 10-9 lead. The winner took the last four points
in a row after a 11-11 tie.
</P>
<P>
Adam Johnson and Karch Kiraly of the United States beat fellows
Ricci Luyties and Sinjin Smith 16-14 in the last game today.
</P>
<P>
The men's gold and bronze medal matches will be on Sunday. The
beach volleyball competition features 100,000 U.S. dollars in
prize money with the winner getting 30,000 dollars. 
</P>
