<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Steels Wins Stage of Tour de France </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, July 24 (Xinhua) -- In the shadow of drug scandals,
Belgian national champion Tom Steels won the 12th stage delayed
two hours in the Tour de France in Tarascon sur Ariege on Friday.
</P>
<P>
However, Steels' victory was overshadowed by the scandals that
smear the sport of cycling.
</P>
<P>
Three of the nine expelled Festina riders, namely world road
race champion Laurent Brochard, Christophe Moreau, both French,
and Armin Meier of Switzerland, admitted taking
performance-enhancing drugs.
</P>
<P>
The remaining six riders, including four-time King of the
Mountains Richard Virenque, and the two assistant team directors,
were released early Friday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Swiss cyclist Armin Meier said on Friday that he had taken the
EPO, becoming the first cyclist in the Tour de France to publicly
admit taking the performance-enhancing substance.
</P>
<P>
And competitors delayed their action for two hours in a
protest, saying the sport of cycling was taking a backseat to the
doping investigation as the tournament was overshadowed by the
drug scandal.
</P>
<P>
Meier, a member of the Festina team that was expelled from the
Tour last week, said he had admitted to taking EPO during police
questioning who, he claimed, had treated him as a criminal and
undressed him to nakedness.
</P>
<P>
"Yes, I said that I had taken EPO, how I took it and why I took
it," he said, "I'm just the victim of a system."
</P>
<P>
However, Meier refused to say if any of his teammates had also
taken the banned substance.
</P>
<P>
In another scandal, Dutch TVM team has two members detained
Friday night over allegations of drug-taking by the team.
</P>
<P>
The team's sporting director Cees Priem and team doctor Andrei
Mikhailov were placed in custody after being questioned in the
southern town of Pamiers.
</P>
<P>
About 100 doses of drugs were found last March in a TVM team
car near Reims, east of Paris. Police did nothing at the time,
but the affair resurfaced in the wake of the Festina scandal that
is rocking the cycling world.
</P>
<P>
Police officials said EPO was found at the team's hotel in
Pamiers during a search on Thursday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980725.0191 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Two Stock Brokerages Announce Merger Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 25 (Xinhua) -- China's two large stock
brokerages, the Shanghai's Guotai Securities and Shenzhen-based
J&AMP;A Securities, announced a merger yesterday to create the biggest
securities firm in China, according to a joint ad issued by the
two companies in the "China Security News" yesterday.
</P>
<P>
The government has yet to approve the proposed merger, China
Daily reported today.
</P>
<P>
The merger resolution has been approved by the boards of
directors of both companies and has now been sent to the relevant
government authorities for approval.
</P>
<P>
The step was taken after several officials of J&AMP;A Securities Co
were accused of breaking the law. They are currently being
investigated by the judicial department.
</P>
<P>
The new company will replace the Shanghai-based Shenyin-Wanguo
to become China's biggest stock trading firm. Shenyin-Wanguo
itself is also a product of a merger in 1996 when the former
International Securities Co, suffering huge losses in treasury
bonds trading, was taken over by Shenyin Securities.
</P>
<P>
According to figures of the Securities Association of China,
J&AMP;A, with total assets of 17.56 billion yuan (two billion US
dollars) was the leading industry profit-earner last year with net
profits amounting to 740.9 million yuan (89.27 million US
dollars). It was also the forth biggest A-share underwriter and
third biggest A-share trader in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Guotai reported 298.37 million yuan (35.95 million US dollars)
in net profits last year with total assets of 5.1 billion yuan
(614 million US dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
