<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mercosur to Deepen Regional Integration Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES, July 24 (Xinhua) -- Member countries of the Latin
America's largest trade bloc, Mercosur, reiterated Friday their
commitment to help quicken the regional integration process with
insistence on the principle of democracy.
</P>
<P>
The presidents of Argentina, Brazil, Paraguay and Uruguay,
which form the South Common Market (Mercosur), reiterated the
commitment in a joint communique issued at the end of their 14th
summit meeting.
</P>
<P>
The one-day summit was held in Argentina's southern outpost
Ushuaia. Also present were presidents of Chile and Bolivia,
Mercosur's two associate members, and visiting South African
President Nelson Mandela.
</P>
<P>
Noting its role in promoting economic growth in the four member
states, the communique spoke highly of the development of
Mercosur. It added that the bloc also helped the entire region
stand up to all challenges triggered by the financial crisis in
Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
Also in the communique, the leaders made clear their support
for the creation of a single currency within the Mercosur, a
proposal initiated by Argentine President Carlos Menem.
</P>
<P>
As for cooperation with the European Union (EU), the communique
said that Mercosur would continue negotiations on the
establishment of a free trade link between the two regions.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the four presidents, together with the presidents
of Chile and Bolivia, signed a political declaration, naming the
territories of the six nations "zone of peace" free of mass
destruction weapons.
</P>
<P>
The six countries promised they would strengthen future
cooperation on defense and security.
</P>
<P>
Also signed in the summit was a series of agreements covering
the fields of trade, justice, education and national
security. These agreements were all documents reached in a
four-day preparatory session at the ministerial level prior to the
summit and ready for signing.
</P>
<P>
The presidents of Mercosur members get together twice per year
and their next summit is expected to be held in Brazil later this
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
