<HEADLINE> Klan Ruled to Pay 37.8 Million Dollars for Hate Message </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 24 (Xinhua) -- A jury decided on Friday the Ku
Klux Klan, a white supremacist group, must pay 37.8 million
U.S. dollars because the group's message of hate incited the
burning of a rural black church in Manning, South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
The award to Macedonia Baptist Church was 12.6 million dollars
more than even its own lawyers had requested. Jurors decided the
church had proved the Klan's rhetoric motivated four former
Klansmen to set the 1995 fire that destroyed the church.
</P>
<P>
The jury of nine blacks and three whites rejected arguments by
the Klan's lawyer that the four acted on their own and the issue
was whether the Klan's speech should be protected by the law.
</P>
<P>
Jonathan Mouzon, the church's pastor, said as quoted by AP,
"This wasn't a monetary thing. This was about taking a stand for
your rights."
</P>
<P>
"There are always going to be people who hate. And lawsuits
like this make it harder for them to operate," said the church's
attorney.
</P>
<P>
Three of the men in prison for the church burning testified,
and two implicated the Klan.
</P>
<P>
"The church fire was Klan business, and we were told we would
not go to jail. We were convinced we were untouchable," one of them
said.
</P>
<P>
Four men pleaded guilty to burning down the church and are
serving prison sentences. A day before the attack, two of them
also torched the Mount Zion AME Church nearby. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
