<HEADLINE> Myanmar, Thailand Sign Tourism Cooperation Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, July 25 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar and Thailand reached an
agreement here Friday on cooperation in tourism between the two
countries, the state-run TV Myanmar reported.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was signed by Myanmar Minister of Hotels and
Tourism Major-General Saw Lwin and visiting Thai Minister to the
Office of the Prime Minister Jurin Laksanawisit.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar is planning to attract more visitors from Thailand that
plays a key role in supplying tourists to the country among its
neighbors and ranked second after Japan.
</P>
<P>
In 1997-98 fiscal year which ended in March, more than 7,000
tourists from Thailand visited Myanmar out of more than 246,000
from 24 countries and regions, according to the official monthly
Economic Indicators.
</P>
<P>
The country has also been receiving a large number of Thai
visitors through Kawthoung at the southern end of the country
bordering Thailand where resorts have been built on some islands.
</P>
<P>
Thailand's investment in Myanmar's hotels and tourism sector,
second only to Singapore, amounted to 200 million U.S. dollars in
eight projects at the end of March this year, compared to a total
of foreign investment of more than 1 billion dollars in the
sector.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Myanmar is also planning to organize a travel show
in Thailand to attract tourists from there following its tourism
promotion campaign launched in Singapore recently. 
</P>
</TEXT>
