<HEADLINE> U.S., Cuba Record Big Wins in Baseball Worlds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, July 24 (Xinhua) -- The United States hit five-homer to
savor its first win while defending champion Cuba justified its
dominance in the pitch at the Baseball World Championships Friday.
</P>
<P>
While the five-homer barrage lifted the Americans to their
first win of 13-6 over Chinese Taipei, five-time champion Cuba impressed the
world by crushing Italy 20-0, including six home runs.
</P>
<P>
So far, Cuba has won 34 straight championships games with its
winning streak dated back to 1986.
</P>
<P>
Eric Munson hit two home runs and John Gall, Ryan Ludwick and
Bobby Hill had one apiece at Messina, Sicily, pushing the
Americans out of last place in Pool A. And Chan Chin Fen clubbed
two homers for the Chinese Taipei that tailed in the group with thr
ee straight defeats.
</P>
<P>
At Bologna, Omar Linares had two round-trippers for Cuba, which
has won its three games here by a total margin of 48-3 and is tied
atop Pool B with Japan and the Dominican Republic, also with 3-0
records.
</P>
<P>
Japan beat South Africa 9-2 at Vicenza, while the Dominican
Republic edged Spain 8-7 at Modena. The other Pool B game saw
Panama blanked China 7-0 at Rimini.
</P>
<P>
In games played at Palermo, Sicily, Australia moved into first
place in Pool A by beating Russia 6-2 for three straight wins,
Canada surprised South Korea 4-1, and Nicaragua dealt the Dutch
its first defeat 13-2.
</P>
<P>
Russia, making its debut at the championships, dropped to 0-3,
while South Korea, runner-up to Cuba in 1994, suffered its first
loss of the tournament. 
</P>
</TEXT>
