<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kunming to Ban Use of Phosphorus Detergents </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, July 25 (Xinhua) -- Kunming, capital of southwest
China's Yunnan Province, will ban sales of phosphorus detergents
in the Dianchi Lake Valley on October 1 as part of an effort to
effectively treat pollution in the nation's sixth largest fresh
water lake.
</P>
<P>
The ban will not only restrict the use of phosphorus detergents
in the lake area with a population of over two million people, but
also require detergent dealers to report their inventories to
industrial and commercial administrations by September 1.
</P>
<P>
Advertising on phosphorus detergents will also be banned.
</P>
<P>
Dianchi Lake, a formerly clear green body of water, is
currently choked by algae which is nourished by major discharges
of phosphorus.
</P>
<P>
The city introduced a program encouraging the use of
phosphorus-free detergents some two years ago, and began levying
fees on sales of phosphorus detergents on January 1, 1997.
</P>
<P>
However, related efforts failed to achieve desired results,
with experts attributing the failure to high prices and the
ineffective cleaning properties of phosphorus-free detergents. The
per ton price for phosphorus-free washing powder hovers around
6,000 yuan, or substantially higher than the 4,000 yuan per ton
for products containing phosphorus.
</P>
<P>
The ban is expected to reinforce the battle against pollution,
according to the local government.
</P>
<P>
Li Guochun, an official in charge of the lake protection, said
that as of October 1, income from illegal sales of the phosphorus
detergents in the areas will be confiscated and offenders will be
subject to fines ranging from 500-5,000 yuan.
</P>
<P>
The province has pledged to carry out the Dianchi pollution
treatment program over the next 18 years. Related efforts will be
carried out with 250 million yuan in funding from the central
government and World Bank loans totalling 150 million US dollars.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980725.0206 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FINA Fails to Reach Verdict in Smith Hearing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, July 24 (Xinhua) -- FINA started its hearing on the
alleged doping case of Irish swimmer Michelle Smith but failed to
reach any decision so far in Lausanne, Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
Smith, triple gold medalist in the Centennial Olympic Games in
Atlanta in 1996, appeared tired before a three-man panel,
answering
questions on the allegations that she had tampered with her urine
samples with achohol earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
If she was found guilty, Smith would face a possible life ban.
For the moment, the Irish swimmers still had to suffer at least
days of nightmares.
</P>
<P>
Harm Bayer, head of the commission, said the panel will review
the case on Saturday and he doubted any decision in days.
</P>
<P>
Smith's lawyer Peter Lennon said a verdict would be announced
in "days or weeks".
</P>
<P>
The hearing lasted four and half a hours as Lennon was given
three hours to present Smith's defense in the closed-door hearing
in Lausanne, headquarters of the swimming world governing body
FINA.
</P>
<P>
Smith appeared in the hearing without the company of her
husband Erik De Bruin, and left the courtroom without meeting the
press circle.
</P>
<P>
In April, FINA said Smith's A sample tested in Barcelona showed
"unequivocal signs of adulteration" and "physical manipulation",
and the analysis of her second sample justified the first findings.
</P>
<P>
Both samples contained a lethal concentration of alcohol,
suggesting an attempt to mask the detection of drugs. But Smith
who underwent the out-of-season test in Ireland on January 10, had
consistently denied taking banned drugs.
</P>
<P>
Under FINA rules, tampering with a urine sample is considered
as serious as taking steroids. The maximum penalty is a life
ban. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980725.0207 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-25 </DATE_TIME>
