<HEADLINE> Swiss Cyclist Admits to Doping in Tour de France </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, July 24 (Xinhua) -- Swiss cyclist Armin Meier said on
Friday that he had taken the EPO, becoming the first cyclist in the Tour de
France to publicly admit taking the performance-enhancing substance.
</P>
<P>
And competitors delayed their action for two hours in a protest, saying the
sport of cycling was taking a backseat to the doping investigation as the
tournament was overshadowed by the drug scandal.
</P>
<P>
Meier, a member of the Festina team that was expelled from the
Tour last week, said he had admitted to taking EPO during police questioning
who, he claimed, had treated him as a criminal and undressed him to nakedness.
</P>
<P>
"Yes, I said that I had taken EPO, how I took it and why I took
it," he said, "I'm just the victim of a system."
</P>
<P>
However, Meier refused to say if any of his teammates had also
taken the banned substance.
</P>
<P>
In another scandal, Dutch TVM team has two members detained
Friday night over allegations of drug-taking by the team.
</P>
<P>
The team's sporting director Cees Priem and team doctor Andrei
Mikhailov were placed in custody after being questioned in the
southern town of Pamiers.
</P>
<P>
About 100 doses of drugs were found last March in a TVM team
car near Reims, east of Paris. Police did nothing at the time,
but the affair resurfaced in the wake of the Festina scandal that
is rocking the cycling world.
</P>
<P>
Police officials said EPO was found at the team's hotel in
Pamiers during a search on Thursday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
