<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Makes 1-2 Finish in Men's 1-Meter Springboard </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, July 24 (Xinhua) -- China's Yu Zhuocheng and Zhou
Yilin met no challenge throughout to sweep the top two medals of
the men's one-meter springboard diving at the Goodwill Games here
Friday.
</P>
<P>
Yu, world 3-meter springboard champion this year, overtook Zhou
in his final dive, winning the gold with a total of 426.24 points.
Zhuo, world silver medalist for the event this year, led the first
five rounds after registering a day-high score of 81.60 on his
second outing. He faded to second position, but still had 26
points to spare than the third placed Mark Ruiz of the United
States, who collected 395.52.
</P>
<P>
The competition was a Chinese affair from the first round,
which saw Zhou ranked first with 63.96 ahead of Yu's 63.18. Ruiz
was listed third, trailig about 1.5 points.
</P>
<P>
Zhou, 24, widened the leading margin after second action, but
Yu narrowed the gap a bit in the third. After the fourth round,
Zhou placed first with 277.86, followed closely by Yu, 277.38.
Ruiz dropped a distance third with 256.02.
</P>
<P>
With the two Chinese fighting for the gold, Ruiz had to hold
off a strong surge from Andreas Wels of Germany in the bronze
battle. The Germany performed excellently in his final two dives,
gaining 72.00 and 73.47, but his efforts came still short, losing
only 2.18 points.
</P>
<P>
"I knew I could win through if I dive good in my last round.
That was the most difficult action and could bring me high point,"
said Yu, who gained his fame in 1993 when he won the World Cup
3-meter springboard title.
</P>
<P>
"I will do my best here to win the 3-meter title," added Yu,
who was selected as the Best Diver of the Year in 1994 by the U.S.
Swimming magzine.
</P>
<P>
Li Dazheng, leader of the Chinese diving team, told Xinhua that
the Chinese divers have strength to take five or six gold medals
here. "But we will meet strong challenge in the men's 3-meter
springboard and the platform." 
</P>
</TEXT>
