<DOCNO> XIE19980725.0222 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sang to Receive Surgery Saturday Morning </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, July 24 (Xinhua) -- Paralyzied Chinese 17-year-old
female gymnast Sang Lan, who injured her spinal cord three days
ago at the current Games, will receive surgery tomorrow morning at
the Nassau County Medical Center, Long Island.
</P>
<P>
"The surgical procedure to stabilize her vertebrae is set for 8
a.m. tomorrow and could last as long as six hours or more. All
consent was secured for us through the Chinese delegation
accompanying Sang Lan," said Doctor Brock Schnebel, Chief Medical
Officer for the Goodwill Games.
</P>
<P>
According to the Chinese delegation, Sang Lan's parents will
arrive here Saturday night. Sang's father Sang Shisheng and mother
Chen Xiufeng heard the tragic news when they were watching T.V. on
July 22 local time.
</P>
<P>
When they couldn't find their darling daughter on the screen,
they began to sense something bad might occur to her. The Chinese
Central TV Station has been transmitting all the competition
programs of the Goodwill Games, so everyone who knows Sang Lan in
Ningbo, a small town near Shanghai, heard the shocking news from
the tv broadcaster.
</P>
<P>
Gu Songhui, top sports official in the city, informed Sang's
parents to prepare for an urgent trip to the United States. Since
Sang Lan is a famous sport star in the local town, many people
flocked her home to console her parents.
</P>
<P>
Sang's parents took a flight to Beijing the following day.
Thanks to the help of the U.S.-Sino governments, they were allowed
to fly here with special permission. The Chinese government let
them go without passports and the U.S. government allowed them to
enter the United States with special visas. Sang Lan is the only
child in her family.
</P>
<P>
Sang Lan, who started gymnastics training at age five, won five
gold medals for Ninbo at the China's Zhejiang Provincial Games.
She was selected into the national team in 1992, and won both the
all-around and vaulting titles at the 1996 Chinese City Games.
</P>
<P>
It was learned that Sang was able to perform some most
difficult vaulting actions in the world, so she was dubbed as "the
vaulting queen" in China.
</P>
<P>
Doctor Schnebel said: "Sang Lan is gaining in her understanding
of what is happening, and is maintaining a good attitude. As you
can imagine, this would be very difficult for anyone, especially a
teenager."
</P>
<P>
The doctor revealed that there has been no neurological change
in her condition at all. "Her mental state is also what we're
watching closely as she deals day-to-day with the injury," he
added.
</P>
<P>
He said Sang Lan has had two dosages of the experimental drug
Sygen so far - one at 10:15 last night and another at 2:30 this
afternoon. Sygen is being administered through a slow-drip IV in
100 milligram dosages over 30-minute periods. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980725.0223 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Two Policemen Killed in Capitol Gunfire Exchange </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 24 (Xinhua) -- A gunman broke through security
barriers at the Capitol Friday afternoon and killed two Capitol
police officers in a heated exchange of gunfire.
</P>
<P>
The suspect was shot and captured and a woman tourist was also
seriously wounded.
</P>
<P>
Federal law enforcement officers said that, based on
preliminary work, authorities believe the man, identified as a
42-year white man from the Midwest, was acting alone when he
invaded the Capitol, filled with summertime tourists, according to
news reports.
</P>
<P>
The slain policemen were Jacob Chestnut, an 18-year veteran of
the Capitol police force, and John Gibson, who had served on the
force for eight years. Both were married and each had three
children.
</P>
<P>
The deaths were confirmed by Sergeant Dan Nichols, spokesman
for the Capitol police. Capitol flags already had been lowered to
half-staff. President Bill Clinton ordered flags at the White
House and other executive buildings lowered as well.
</P>
<P>
Both police officers were declared dead at nearby hospitals.
Nichols said one of the officers was on duty at the entrance, and
was shot there. The other was killed just inside the Capitol.
</P>
<P>
The shootings occurred near the suite of offices occupied by
Representative Tom DeLay of Texas, the House Republican whip. He
was inside the office when the gunfire burst out in the hallway.
</P>
<P>
The wounded tourist was identified as Angela Dickerson, 24, and
was reported in serious condition at George Washington University
Hospital.
</P>
<P>
The suspect was expected to survive. He was from Illinois and
had moved to Montana two or three years ago, an official said.
</P>
<P>
Clinton, who was at Camp David, Maryland, issued a statement
saying he was "deeply disturbed" by the bloodshed at "the people's
house, a place where visitors and workers should not have to fear
violence."
</P>
<P>
Clinton telephoned Speaker Newt Gingrich after learning of the
shootings, and Gingrich also spoke by phone with Democratic Leader
Dick Gephardt, who had left the Capitol by the time the attack
occurred.
</P>
<P>
Gingrich also spoke with Gibson's and Chestnut's families and
planned to visit them to express his condolences, said an aide.
</P>
<P>
DeLay issued a statement of gratitude for the work of the
officers, saying of officer Gibson, "I have no doubt that John
saved the lives of many people today." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980725.0224 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Market Exchange Rates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 25 (Xinhua) -- The People's Bank of China today
issued the market exchange rates in RMB yuan against three major
currencies. The middle price of RMB against convertible currencies
is mainly based on the closing price of the preceding interbank
trading.
</P>
<P>
The designated foreign exchange trading banks will decide the
exchange rates in RMB yuan against other convertible currencies
according to the tone of the international exchange market and the
rules of the People's Bank of China.
</P>
