<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tour Riders Delay Twelfth Stage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, July 24 (Xinhua) -- Tour de France riders on Friday held
up the start of the 12th stage of the race in protest over a drugs
scandal involving the top-ranking Festina team.
</P>
<P>
The stage finally began two hours late after frantic talks
between cyclists and race officials.
</P>
<P>
Just minutes before the stage was due to start, world No.1
cyclist Laurent Jalabert of France addressed race officials on the
tour radio station, saying the riders had decided to boycott
Friday's stage.
</P>
<P>
Race director Jean-Marie Leblanc immediately announced the
start of the 222 kilometre-stage from Tarascon to Cap D'Agde would
be delayed while he held urgent talks with riders and team
officials.
</P>
<P>
The scandal erupted when performance-enhancing drugs were
seized from a Festina car and the team later expelled from the
race. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
